# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bbc-one
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bbc-one/1080i] In TV streaming, high-definition television (HDTV) and video display technology, **1080i** is a video display format with 1080 lines of vertical resolution and interlaced scanning method.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] This format was once a standard in HDTV.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] It was particularly used for broadcast television because it can deliver high-resolution images without needing excessive bandwidth.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] This format is used in the SMPTE 292M standard.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] The number "1080" in 1080i refers to the number of horizontal lines that make up the vertical resolution of the display.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] Each of these lines contributes to the overall detail and clarity of the image.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] This is a technique where the image is not displayed all at once.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] Instead, the frame is split into two fields.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] One field contains the odd-numbered lines, and the other field contains the even-numbered lines.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] These fields are displayed in rapid succession, giving the appearance of a full image to the human eye.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] The interlacing technique was developed to improve the motion portrayal of images without doubling the required bandwidth.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] This is particularly useful in broadcasting, where bandwidth efficiency is crucial.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] The frame rate is typically 50 or 60 fields per second, depending on the region.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] This effectively means 25 or 30 frames per second when the fields are combined.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] A key difference between 1080i and 1080p is how the lines of resolution are displayed.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] Both offer 1920x1080 pixels, but the display method is different.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] In 1080p, the "p" stands for progressive scan.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] Each frame is drawn line by line, from top to bottom, creating a complete image in a single pass.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] This results in a sharper and more stable picture, especially in fast-moving scenes.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] On the other hand, 1080i uses an interlaced method.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] The two fields that make up a frame are captured at slightly different times, leading to a misalignment in fast-moving parts of the image.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] This can cause artifacts like "combing," where fast-moving objects appear to have a serrated edge.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] However, 1080i has been preferred in broadcast television due to its lower bandwidth requirements, making it more efficient for over-the-air or cable transmission.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] The origins of 1080i can be traced from Multiple sub-Nyquist sampling encoding, a Japanese analog high-definition television system.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] 1080i emerged as a leading standard for HDTV broadcasts.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] The ATSC (Advanced Television Systems Committee) standards and the DVB (Digital Video Broadcasting) standards allowed for the transmission of 1080i video signals.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] The adoption of 1080i was particularly significant in sports broadcasting.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] The higher resolution allowed for more detail and clarity, especially in large stadium shots and fast-paced action.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] The format's efficiency in utilizing available bandwidth made it a practical choice for broadcasters.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] However, it required more complex processing on the receiving end to deinterlace the image for display on progressive-scan screens.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] Overall, 1080i played a crucial role in the early days of HDTV.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] It bridged the gap between standard-definition broadcasts and the high-definition future that would soon become the norm.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] While its use has diminished with the rise of 1080p and 4K resolutions, 1080i remains an important milestone in the evolution of television technology.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] This means that each video frame has 1,920 pixels horizontally and 1,080 pixels vertically.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] This results in over two million individual pixels per frame.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] This high resolution is why 1080i is called "high-definition".
[src:bbc-one/1080i] It offers a significant improvement over standard-definition formats, which typically have much lower pixel counts.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] The 1920x1080 resolution allows for greater detail and clarity in images.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] This makes it ideal for larger screens where higher pixel density is essential to maintain image quality.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] The increased resolution is particularly noticeable in fine details such as textures, text, and intricate patterns.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] These can be rendered with much greater accuracy than in lower-resolution formats.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] This refers to how each video frame is displayed.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] Instead of showing the entire frame at once, the interlacing technique divides each frame into two separate fields.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] The first field contains all the odd-numbered lines (1, 3, 5, etc.), and the second field contains all the even-numbered lines (2, 4, 6, etc.).
[src:bbc-one/1080i] These two fields are displayed one after the other.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] The odd lines are shown first, followed by the even lines.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] This happens very quickly, around 50 or 60 fields per second.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] The human eye sees these two fields as a single, continuous image.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] The main advantage of interlacing is that it allows for a higher frame rate without needing more bandwidth.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] This results in smoother motion, especially for content with moderate to fast movement, like sports broadcasts.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] However, interlacing also has some drawbacks.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] Since the two fields are captured at slightly different times, fast-moving objects can appear misaligned between the two fields.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] This creates a visual artifact called "combing." This can reduce image quality, especially in scenes with a lot of motion.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] Modern display devices often use deinterlacing algorithms to combine the two fields into a single progressive image before displaying it.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] The frame rate of 1080i is usually 50 or 60 Hz.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] In areas using the PAL or SECAM standards, like Europe and parts of Asia, the frame rate is 50 Hz.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] In regions using NTSC, like North America and Japan, the frame rate is 60 Hz.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] The frame rate refers to how often a new field is shown per second.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] At 50 Hz, 50 fields are shown each second.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] This results in 25 full frames per second when the odd and even fields are combined.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] At 60 Hz, 59.94 fields are shown per second.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] This results in 29.97 full frames per second.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] Interlacing affects how motion is perceived in 1080i.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] Since each field represents a slightly different moment in time, motion can appear smoother compared to lower frame rate progressive scans.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] However, this also means 1080i can struggle with fast-moving scenes.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] The interlaced fields might not perfectly align, leading to motion artifacts.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] The European Broadcasting Union (EBU) prefers to use the resolution and *frame rate* (not field rate) separated by a slash, as in *1080i/29.97* and *1080i/25*, likewise 480i/29.97 and 576i/25.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] The 1080i video signals can be carried by four main digital television broadcast systems: ATSC, DVB, ISDB and DTMB.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] In both ATSC and DVB systems, the 1080i signal is compressed using codecs like MPEG-2 or H.264 to reduce the bandwidth required for transmission.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] In the United States, 1080i is the preferred format for most broadcasters, with Warner Bros.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] Discovery, Paramount Global, and Comcast owned networks broadcasting in the format, along with most smaller broadcasters.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] Only Fox- and Disney-owned television networks, along with MLB Network and a few other cable networks, use 720p as the preferred format for their networks; A&E Networks channels converted from 720p to 1080i sometime in 2013 due to acquired networks already transmitting in the 1080i format.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] This also allows local newscasts on these ABC affiliates to be produced in the higher resolution (especially for weather forecasting presentation purposes for map clarity) to match the picture quality of their 1080i competitors.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] Motion pictures shot on film to fit a 16:9 widescreen format (1.78:1) are typically intended to be played back at 24 frames per second.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] When telecined and played back at the PAL standard 25 frames per second, films run 4.16% faster than the original, and 4.27083% faster than the NTSC film standard 23.976023976 frames per second.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] High-definition television (HDTV) broadcast standards utilize 1080i (interlaced) or 720p (progressive) formats, typically offering 1920x1080 resolution.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] Key, region-specific formats include 1080i25 for PAL (50 fields/second), 1080i30 for NTSC (60 fields/second), and 1080i24 for film, often converted via telecine for 25/30 frames per second, 1080i50/60 broadcasts.
[src:bbc-one/1080i] PAL speed-up does not occur on footage intended for playback at 25 frames per second.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] 1080p video signals are supported by ATSC standards in the United States and DVB standards in Europe.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] Applications of the 1080p standard include television broadcasts, Blu-ray Discs, smartphones, Internet content such as YouTube videos and Netflix TV shows and movies, consumer-grade televisions and projectors, computer monitors and video game consoles.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] Small camcorders, smartphones and digital cameras can capture still and moving images in 1080p resolution.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] Any display device that advertises 1080p typically refers to the ability to accept a 1080p signal and display it with a native resolution of at least 1080 lines vertically (as well as the ability to upscale lower-resolution material to 1080p).
[src:bbc-one/1080p] This means that the display is not over-scanning, under-scanning, or reinterpreting the signal to a lower resolution.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] The HD ready 1080p logo program, by DigitalEurope, requires that certified TV sets support 1080p 24 fps, 1080p 25 fps, 1080p 50 fps, and 1080p 60 fps formats, among other requirements, with fps meaning frames per second.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] For live broadcast applications, a high-definition progressive scan format operating at 1080p at 50 or 60 frames per second was being evaluated as a future standard for moving picture acquisition, although 24 fps was used for shooting movies.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] Most current revisions of SMPTE 372M, SMPTE 424M and EBU Tech 3299 require YCbCr color space and 4:2:2 chroma subsampling for transmitting 1080p50 (nominally 2.08 Gbit/s) and 1080p60 signal.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] In the United States, the original ATSC standards for HDTV supported 1080p video, but only at the frame rates of 23.976, 24, 25, 29.97 and 30 frames per second (colloquially known as **1080p24**, **1080p25** and **1080p30**).
[src:bbc-one/1080p] Such frame rates require H.264/AVC *High Profile Level 4.2*, while standard HDTV frame rates only require Level 4.0.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] This update is not expected to result in widespread availability of 1080p60 programming, since most of the existing digital receivers in use would only be able to decode the older, less-efficient MPEG-2 codec, and because there is a limited amount of bandwidth for subchannels.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] In Europe, 1080p25 signals have been supported by the DVB suite of broadcasting standards.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] The 1080p50 format is considered to be a future-proof production format and, eventually, a future broadcasting format.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] 1080p50 broadcasting should require the same bandwidth as 1080i50 signal and only 15–20% more than that of 720p50 signal due to increased compression efficiency, though 1080p50 production requires more bandwidth or more efficient codecs such as JPEG 2000, high-bitrate MPEG-2, or H.264/AVC and HEVC.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] EBU requires that legacy MPEG-4 AVC decoders should avoid crashing in the presence of SVC or 1080p50 (and higher resolution) packets.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] The ITU-T BT.2100 standard that includes Advanced 1080p video was subsequently published in July 2016.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] In practice, 1080p typically refers to a 1920 × 1080p raster with a 16:9 picture aspect ratio.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] The following is a list of other resolutions with a picture height of 1080 lines that are sometimes referred as 1080p.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] In the United States, 1080p over-the-air broadcasts are currently available in select stations in some cities in the US via ATSC 3.0 multiplex stations where as ATSC 3.0 is currently rolling out throughout the U.S.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] The majority of the stations that broadcast at 1080p are CBS and NBC stations and affiliates.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] All other stations do not broadcast at 1080p and usually broadcast at 720p60 (including when simulcasting in ATSC 3.0) or 1080i60 (outside of ATSC 3.0) encoded with MPEG-2.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] There is also technical restrictions with ATSC 3.0 multiplex stations that prevent stations from airing at 1080p.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] While converting to ATSC 3.0 is voluntary by TV Stations, there is no word when any of the major networks will consider airing at 1080p in the foreseeable future on a national scale, although they are required to broadcast ATSC signals for at least five years thereafter.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] However, satellite services (e.g., DirecTV, XstreamHD and Dish Network) use the 1080p/24-30 format with MPEG-4 AVC/H.264 encoding for pay-per-view movies that are downloaded in advance via satellite or on-demand via broadband.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] For material that originates from a progressive scanned 24 frame/s source (such as film), MPEG-2 lets the video be coded as 1080p24, irrespective of the final output format.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] These progressively-coded frames are tagged with metadata (literally, fields of the PICTURE header) instructing a decoder how to perform a 3:2 pulldown to interlace them.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] While the formal output of the MPEG-2 decoding process from such stations is 1080i60, the actual content is coded as 1080p24 and can be viewed as such (using a process known as inverse telecine) since no information is lost even when the broadcaster performs the 3:2 pulldown.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] In June 2016, German television stations began broadcasting 1080p50 high-definition video on eight channels via the HEVC-encoded DVB-T2 protocol.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] A total of 40 channels were available on March 29, 2017 (Phase 1).
[src:bbc-one/1080p] Blu-ray Discs are able to hold 1080p HD content, and most movies released on Blu-ray Disc produce a full 1080p HD picture when the player is connected to a 1080p HDTV via an HDMI cable.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] Generally this type of video runs at 30 to 40 megabits per second, compared to the 3.5 megabits per second for conventional standard definition broadcasts.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] Smartphones with 1080p Full HD display have been available on the market since 2012.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] As of 2014, it is the standard for mid-range to high-end smartphones, with many flagship devices using even higher resolutions, such as Quad HD (1440p) or Ultra HD (2160p).
[src:bbc-one/1080p] Several websites, including YouTube, allow videos to be uploaded in the 1080p format.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] YouTube streams 1080p content at approximately 4 megabits per second compared to Blu-ray's 30 to 40 megabits per second.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] Digital distribution services like Hulu and HBO Max also deliver 1080p content, such as movies available on Blu-ray Disc or from broadcast sources.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] This can include distribution services like peer-to-peer websites and public or private tracking networks.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] Netflix has been offering high quality 1080p content in the US and other countries through select internet providers since 2013.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] As of 2012, most consumer televisions being sold provide 1080p inputs, mainly via HDMI, and support full high-definition resolutions.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] 1080p resolution is available in all types of television, including plasma, LCD, DLP front and rear projection and LCD projection.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] For displaying film-based 1080i60 signals, a scheme called 3:2 pulldown reversal (reverse telecine) is beginning to appear in some newer 1080p displays, which can produce a true 1080p quality image from film-based 1080i60 programs.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] Similarly, 25fps content broadcast at 1080i50 may be deinterlaced to 1080p content with no loss of quality or resolution.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] AV equipment manufacturers have adopted the term *Full HD* to mean a set can display all available HD resolutions up to 1080p.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] The term is misleading, however, because it does not guarantee the set is capable of rendering digital video at all frame rates encoded in source files with 1920 X 1080 pixel resolution.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] Most notably, a "Full HD" set is not guaranteed to support the 1080p24 format, leading to consumer confusion.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] DigitalEurope (formerly EICTA) maintains the HD ready 1080p logo program that requires the certified TV sets to support 1080p24, 1080p50, and 1080p60, without overscan/underscan and picture distortion.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] Most widescreen cathode-ray tube (CRT) and liquid-crystal display (LCD) monitors can natively display 1080p content.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] For example, widescreen WUXGA monitors support 1920 × 1200 resolution, which can display a pixel for pixel reproduction of the 1080p (1920 × 1080) format.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] Additionally, many 23, 24, and 27-inch (690 mm) widescreen LCD monitors use 1920 × 1200 as their native resolution; 30 inch displays can display beyond 1080p at up to 2560 × 1600 (1600p).
[src:bbc-one/1080p] Many 27" monitors have native resolutions of 2560 × 1440 and hence operate at 1440p.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] Sony has their first and formerly Vaio 1080p laptop, VPCCB17FG, in 2011, and since Asus also has their first 4K laptop GL502 which was formerly branded Republic of Gamers in 2017, 1080p has also become the nowadays lowest standard for laptops.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] While Microsoft's original Xbox, launched as part of the sixth generation of video game consoles in 2001, could support a 1080i output in limited circumstances, support for 1080p began with the launch of the seventh generation of home video game consoles in 2005.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] Both the Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 were capable of outputting at 1080p, with only the Wii unable to support the resolution.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] All home video game consoles launched as part of the eighth generation, which began in 2012 with the launch of the Wii U, were capable of 1080p outputs.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] Mid-generation hardware revisions and new models introduced by Sony and Microsoft to their respective PlayStation 4 and Xbox One consoles added the capability of outputting at 4K UHD — well beyond 1080p.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] Moreover, this mid-generational improvement in computing power also represented a leap in the ability of video game consoles to render gaming content at a 1080p resolution or higher, rather than relying on upscaling.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] This trend continued with the launch of the current ninth generation of video game consoles in 2020, in which both Sony's PlayStation 5 and Microsoft's Xbox Series X were advertised as including 8K UHD support.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] As of 2024, however, neither console yet supports outputting the standard and PlayStation 5 packaging no longer advertises the feature.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] The Nintendo Switch console displays in resolutions up to 1080p when docked, while the successor console, Nintendo Switch 2, displays in 1080p when undocked, and up to 4K when docked.
[src:bbc-one/1080p] Many cameras—professional and consumer still, action and video cameras, including DSLR cameras—and other devices with built-in cameras such as laptops, smartphones and tablet computers, can capture 1080p24, 1080p25, 1080p30 or 1080p60 video, often encoding it in progressive segmented frame format.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The **1948 Summer Olympics**, officially the **Games of the XIV Olympiad** and officially branded as **London 1948**, were an international multi-sport event held from 29 July to 14 August 1948 in London, United Kingdom.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Following a twelve-year hiatus caused by the outbreak of World War II, these were the first Summer Olympics held since the 1936 Games in Berlin.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The 1940 Olympic Games had been scheduled for Tokyo and then for Helsinki, while the 1944 Olympic Games had been provisionally planned for London.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] This was the second time London hosted the Olympic Games, having previously hosted them in 1908, making it the second city to host the Summer Olympics twice (after Paris).
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The Olympics would return again to London 64 years later in 2012, making London the first city to host the games three times, and the only such city until Paris, who hosted their third games in 2024, and Los Angeles, who will host theirs in 2028.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The 1948 Olympic Games were also the first of two summer Games held under the IOC presidency of Sigfrid Edström.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The 1948 Summer Olympics were the only Summer Olympics to be held in the 1940s, as the 1940 and 1944 Summer Olympics were cancelled due to World War II.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] It was also the first Summer Olympics that took place during the Cold War.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The 1948 Olympics came to be known as the "Austerity Games" due to the difficult economic climate and the rationing imposed in the aftermath of World War II.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] A record 59 nations were represented by 4,104 athletes, 3,714 men, and 390 women in 19 sport disciplines.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Germany and Japan were not invited to participate in the games; the Soviet Union was invited but chose not to send any athletes, sending observers instead to prepare for the 1952 Olympics.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Israel requested to participate (symbolically represented by Raya Bronstein and Frieda Berson-Lichtblau) but was denied as the International Olympic Committee did not yet recognize the country, while the Olympic mandate of Palestine expired.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] This in turn shifted the view of the Arab countries who had intended to boycott the event and now decided to take part.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] One of the star performers at the 1948 Games was Dutch sprinter Fanny Blankers-Koen.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Dubbed the "Flying Housewife", the thirty-year-old mother of two won four gold medals in athletics.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] In the decathlon, Bob Mathias of the United States became the youngest male ever to win an Olympic track and field gold medal at the age of seventeen.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The most individual medals were won by Veikko Huhtanen of Finland, who took three golds, a silver and a bronze in men's gymnastics.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The United States topped the medal table.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] In June 1939, the International Olympic Committee (IOC) awarded the 1944 Olympic Summer Games to London, ahead of Rome, Detroit, Budapest, Lausanne, Helsinki, Montreal and Athens.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] World War II stopped the plans and the Games were cancelled so London again stood as a candidate for 1948.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Great Britain almost handed the 1948 games to the United States due to post-war financial and rationing problems, but King George VI said that hosting the Olympics would help to restore Britain from World War II.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The official report of the London Olympics shows that London was not pressed to run the Games against its will.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] and saw the president of the International Olympic Committee to discuss the question of London being chosen for this great event.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] As a result, an investigating committee was set up by the British Olympic Council to work out in some detail the possibility of holding the Games.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] should be invited to apply for the allocation of the Games in 1948.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] In June 1946 the IOC, through a postal vote, gave the summer Games to London and the winter competition to St Moritz.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] London was selected ahead of Baltimore, Minneapolis, Lausanne, Los Angeles, and Philadelphia.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] London, which had previously hosted the 1908 Summer Olympics, became the second city to host the Olympics twice; Paris hosted the event in 1900 and 1924.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] London later became the first city to host the Olympics for a third time when the city hosted the 2012 Summer Olympics.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Lord Burghley, a gold medal winner at the 1928 Olympics, member of the International Olympic Committee (IOC), and president of the Amateur Athletics Association was named Chairman of the Organising and Executive Committees.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The other members of the committees were: Colonel Evan Hunter, General Secretary of the British Olympic Association, and Chief de mission for Great Britain; Lord Aberdare, the other British member of the IOC; Sir Noel Curtis-Bennett; Alderman H.E.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Emrys Lloyd, who became the committee's legal advisor; C.B.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Cowley of the London Press and Advertising; R.B.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Studdert, managing director of the Army & Navy Stores; A.E.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Porritt, a member of the IOC for New Zealand who resided in London; S.F.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Rous, Secretary of The Football Association; and Jack Beresford.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Olympic pictograms were introduced for the first time.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] There were twenty of them—one for each Olympic sport and three separate pictograms for the arts competition, the opening ceremony and the closing ceremony.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] They were called "Olympic symbols" and intended for use on tickets.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The background of each pictogram resembled an escutcheon.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Olympic pictograms appeared again 16 years later, and were used at all subsequent Summer Olympics.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] At the time of the Games, food, petrol and building were still subject to the rationing imposed during the war in Britain; because of this the 1948 Olympics came to be known as the "Austerity Games".
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Athletes were given the same increased rations as dockers and miners, 5,467 calories a day instead of the normal 2,600.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Building an Olympic Village was deemed too expensive, and athletes were housed in existing accommodation.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Male competitors stayed at RAF camps in Uxbridge and West Drayton, and an Army camp in Richmond Park; female competitors in London colleges.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Lord Burghley unfurled the Olympic Flag at the Richmond Park camp at an opening ceremony in July as Minister of Works, Charles Key, declared the camp open.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] These were the first games to be held following the death of Pierre de Coubertin, founder of the International Olympic Committee, in 1937.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] They were also the last to include an arts competition, which took place at the Victoria and Albert Museum.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Nicknamed "relay of peace" due to crossing through several countries in Europe to represent their union after the Second World War, the torch relay for these games took place from 17 to 29 July 1948, with a distance of 3,160 kilometres (1,960 mi) and 1,416 torchbearers.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] There were three types of torches: the standard one made of aluminium and powered by solid fuel, a special one powered by butane gas (used aboard HMS *Whitesand Bay*) and a third one used in the Wembley stadium, made of stainless steel and powered by a magnesium candle.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The journey began with the lighting of the flame in Olympia.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Due to the civil war taking place in Greece, the Greek part of the relay went directly to Corfu, where HMS *Whitesand Bay* picked the flame to transport it to Bari.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] From there, the flame crossed Italy, Switzerland, France, Luxembourg and Belgium.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] After a boat trip from Calais to Dover (aboard of HMS *Bicester*), the flame traveled to several towns in Southeast England until the arrival at Wembley for the Opening ceremony.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Army bands began playing at 2 pm for the 85,000 spectators in Empire Stadium at Wembley Park.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The international and national organisers arrived at 2.35 pm and King George VI and Queen Elizabeth, with Queen Mary and other members of the Royal Family, at 2.45 pm.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Fifteen minutes later the competitors entered the stadium in a procession that took 50 minutes.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The last team was that of the United Kingdom.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] A visionary dream has today become a glorious reality.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] At the end of the worldwide struggle in 1945, many institutions and associations were found to have withered and only the strongest had survived.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] How, many wondered, had the great Olympic Movement prospered?
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] At 4 pm, the time shown on the clock tower on the London Games symbol, the King declared the Games open, 2,500 pigeons were set free and the Olympic Flag raised to its 35 ft (11 m) flagpole at the end of the stadium.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The Royal Horse Artillery sounded a 21-gun salute to welcome the last runner in the Torch Relay: John Mark, a British track and field sprinter and student at the University of Cambridge with impressive Olympian good looks.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Mark ran a lap of the track – created with cinders from the domestic coal fires of Leicester – and climbed the steps to the Olympic cauldron.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] After saluting the crowd, he turned and lit the flame.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] After more speeches, Donald Finlay of the British team (given his RAF rank of Wing Commander) took the Olympic Oath on behalf of all competitors.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The National Anthem was sung and the massed athletes turned and marched out of the stadium, led by Greece, tailed by Britain.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Thus were launched the Olympic Games of London, under the most happy auspices.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony and over 60 hours of Games coverage was broadcast live on BBC television, which was then officially available only in the London area.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] However, the BBC's transmissions could be received much further away in the right conditions, and some of the Games were watched by at least one viewer in the Channel Islands.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The BBC's official report on the coverage estimated that an average of half a million viewers watched each of their Olympic broadcasts.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The BBC paid £1,000 for the broadcasting rights.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Of the live television coverage, only a small section of the opening ceremony broadcast still exists in the archives.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] However, various filmed reports shot for the BBC's *Television Newsreel* program do also still exist.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The 1948 Summer Olympics featured 136 medal events, covering 23 disciplines in 17 different sports and in arts.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] In the list below, the number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] These Games also included Lacrosse and Swedish (Ling) gymnastics as demonstration sports.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Empire Stadium was the venue for 33 athletics events at the Games; 24 for men and nine for women.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Of these, four were making their Olympic debut – the men's 10 km walk, and the women's 200 metres, long jump and shot put.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] A total of 754 athletes from 53 countries participated in athletics.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Fanny Blankers-Koen of the Netherlands, a 30-year-old mother of two children nicknamed "The Flying Housewife", won four gold medals, in the 100 metres, 200 metres, 80 metre hurdles, and 4 x 100 metre relay.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] As world record holder in the long jump and high jump Blankers-Koen may have been able to win further medals but, at this time, female athletes were limited to three individual events.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Duncan White won the first medal of any kind for Sri Lanka (then Ceylon) when he finished second in the 400 metre hurdles.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Arthur Wint became the first Jamaican to win an Olympic gold medal, in the men's 400 metres; he also won silver in the men's 800 metres.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Audrey Patterson became the first African-American woman to win a medal, winning bronze in a track and field event.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] A few days later Alice Coachman became the first woman of colour in the world and the first African-American woman to win a gold medal in track and field in the history of the modern Olympics with a jump of 1.68 m (5' 61⁄4").
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] She also was the only American woman to win an athletics gold medal during the 1948 Olympics.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The marathon saw a dramatic finish with the first man to enter the stadium, Etienne Gailly of Belgium, exhausted and nearly unable to run.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] While he was struggling, Argentinian athlete Delfo Cabrera and Tom Richards of Great Britain passed him, with Cabrera winning the gold medal and Richards obtaining the silver.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Gailly managed to recover enough to cross the line for the bronze.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The decathlon was won by 17-year-old Bob Mathias of the United States.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Categories: sports-related architecture, literature, music, painting, and sculpture.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] These Olympics were the last time art competitions were considered Olympic events.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Basketball made its second appearance as a medal sport, appearing as an indoor competition for the first time after poor weather disrupted the matches at the 1936 Berlin Games.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The event, for men only, was contested by 23 nations split into four pools for the preliminary round; the top two in each pool advanced to the quarterfinals with the other teams entering playoffs for the minor placings.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The United States and France reached the final which was won by the Americans 65–21 to claim the gold medal.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] This was the second of the United States' seven consecutive gold medals in Olympic men's and women's basketball.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Brazil defeated Mexico 52–47 to claim bronze.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Eight different classifications were contested ranging from flyweight, for boxers weighing less than 51 kg, to heavyweight, for boxers over 80 kg.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] South Africa, Argentina and Hungary each won two gold medals.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Nine events were contested, eight for men and one for women.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] This marked the first time that a women's canoeing event had been contested in the Olympics.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Sweden won four gold medals (two by Gert Fredriksson) and Czechoslovakia three.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Six events were contested – two road bicycle racing events and four track cycling events.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] No women's cycling events were contested.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] France won three gold medals and Italy two, while Great Britain captured five medals overall, but none were gold.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Four diving events were contested, two for men, and two for women.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The events are labelled as 3 metre springboard and 10 metre platform by the International Olympic Committee but appeared on the 1948 Official Report as *springboard diving* and *highboard diving*, respectively.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] All four gold medals, and 10 out of 12 awarded in total, were won by the United States.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Victoria Manalo Draves, who won both gold medals in the women's events, and Sammy Lee, who took a gold and a bronze in the men's events, became the first Asian Americans to win gold medals at an Olympic Games.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Six gold medals were awarded in equestrian, individual and team dressage, individual and team eventing and individual and team show jumping.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Harry Llewellyn and Foxhunter, who would claim a gold medal in Helsinki, won bronze in the team jumping event.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Seven events were contested, six for men and one for women.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Ilona Elek, who had won the women's foil competition in Berlin, was one of only two competitors to successfully defend an Olympic title in London.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Elek's sister, Margit, placed sixth in the same event.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Edoardo Mangiarotti won three medals, two silver and a bronze, having previously won a gold medal in the 1936 Games.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Throughout his career the Italian won 13 Olympic fencing medals and 27 world championship medals, both of which remain records.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Thirteen nations participated in the field hockey competition.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The tournament was ultimately won by India, who defeated Great Britain to claim the country's first gold medal as an independent nation under captain Kishan Lal and Vice-Captain Kunwar Digvijay Singh.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Eighteen teams entered the football competition at these Olympics.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Due to the rise of the professional game during the 12 years since the Berlin Olympics the number of talented amateurs for teams to select from was reduced.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The gold medal was won by Sweden, who defeated Yugoslavia 3–1 in the final.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Denmark defeated hosts Great Britain, managed by Matt Busby of Manchester United, 5–3 to win the bronze medal.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] In the tournament's 18 matches a total of 102 goals were scored; an average 5.66 goals per match.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The joint top scorers with seven goals each were Gunnar Nordahl of Sweden and Denmark's John Hansen.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Nordahl and Swedish teammates Gunnar Gren and Nils Liedholm went on to play for A.C.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Milan and together were nicknamed Gre-No-Li.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] This was the first international football tournament ever to be broadcast on television, with the two semi-finals, the bronze medal match and the final all being shown live in full by the BBC.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Nine events were contested, eight for men, and one for women.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] In the men's pommel horse, a tie was declared between three competitors, all Finns, and no medals other than gold were awarded in this event.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Finland won six gold medals overall, and Switzerland three.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Lacrosse was an exhibition sport at these Olympics.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] An English team composed of players from various universities played a U.S. team represented by Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute at the Empire Stadium.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Only one modern pentathlon event was contested, the five component sports– riding, fencing, shooting, swimming, and running- being held over six days.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Scoring was by point-for-place system across the five phases with the winner being the athlete with the lowest combined ranking.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The sport's international federation, the Union Internationale de Pentathlon Moderne was founded during the Games, on 3 August 1948.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Sweden won two medals in the event; William Grut won the gold, with a final points total of 16, and Gösta Gärdin took bronze.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] American George Moore won the silver medal.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Seven rowing events were contested, all open to men only.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Great Britain and the United States each claimed two gold medals.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The events were held on the River Thames at Henley, over the same course as the Henley Royal Regatta.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The sailing events at the Games took place in Torquay, in the southwest of Great Britain.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Five events were contested, with the United States winning four total medals.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] One of host nation Great Britain's three gold medals at the Games came in the Swallow class from Stewart Morris and David Bond.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] In the Firefly class Danish sailor Paul Elvstrøm won gold the despite the Danish Olympic Committee having misgivings about sending him to compete as the 18-year-old could speak no English.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] This was the first of four consecutive Olympics with a gold medal for Elvstrøm.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Four events were contested, all open to both men and women, although all medals were won by men.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] In the 50 metre rifle, prone position, only two points separated the top three competitors.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Károly Takács had been a member of the Hungary's world champion pistol shooting team in 1938 when a grenade shattered his right hand – his pistol hand.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Takács taught himself to shoot with his left hand and, 10 years after his injury, he won an Olympic gold medal in the rapid-fire pistol event.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Eleven events were contested, six for men and five for women.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The United States won eight gold medals, including all six men's events, and 15 medals in total.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Eighteen nations fielded a team in these games, which were ultimately won by Italy, who were undefeated throughout.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The tournament was conducted in a mult-tier bracket, with the best four teams from the group stages participating in a final round-robin bracket.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Silver was claimed by Hungary, and bronze by the Netherlands.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Six events were contested, all for men only.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] These games marked the addition of the bantamweight class to the Olympic programme, the first change to the programme since 1920.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The United States won four gold medals, and eight overall; the remaining two gold medals were claimed by Egypt.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Sixteen wrestling events were held, eight Greco-Roman and eight freestyle.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Both categories were dominated by two nations.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Turkey was the most successful nation with six gold medals followed by Sweden receiving 5 gold medals.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] These two teams claimed 24 total medals, in other words half of the total medals given.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] London was the first Olympics to have a political defection.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Marie Provazníková, the 57-year-old Czechoslovak President of the International Gymnastics Federation, refused to return home, citing "lack of freedom" after the Czechoslovak coup in February led to the country's inclusion in the Soviet Bloc.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] For the 1948 Olympics, the Technicolor Corporation devised a bipack colour filming process – dubbed "Technichrome" – whereby hundreds of hours of film documented the events in colour, without having to use expensive and heavy Technicolor cameras.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Slightly over 2,000 journalists attended the 1948 Games.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] A cinder track was laid inside Empire Stadium and all other venues were adapted.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] For the first time at the Olympics swimming events were held undercover, at the 8000 capacity Empire Pool.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] As the pool was longer than the standard Olympic length of 50 metres a platform was constructed across the pool which both shortened it and housed officials.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] In 2010 one of the last remaining venues from the Games, the Herne Hill Velodrome where cycling events were staged, was saved when a new 15-year lease was agreed meaning that repairs could take place.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Campaigners and users of the track had feared that it would be forced to close as it was in desperate need of refurbishment.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Thirteen made their first official appearance: British Guiana (now Guyana), Burma (now Myanmar), Ceylon (now Sri Lanka), Iraq, Jamaica, Korea, Lebanon, Pakistan, Puerto Rico, Singapore, Syria, Trinidad and Tobago, and Venezuela.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] It was the first time that Australia, New Zealand, Philippines, India and Pakistan competed as fully independent nations at the Olympic Games.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Germany and Japan, under Allied military occupations, were not allowed to send athletes to the games.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Due to continuing labour shortages, German prisoners of war were used for the construction of the facilities for the games, in particular Olympic Way.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Italy, although originally an Axis power, had defected to the Allies in 1943 following Benito Mussolini being deposed, and was allowed to send athletes.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The Soviet Union was invited but chose not to send any athletes, sending observers instead to prepare for the 1952 Olympics.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The nations that returned to the games were Cuba, Iran (The last participation of a Persian athlete was in Paris 1900), Ireland, Panama and Spain.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Other nations, besides Germany and Japan, that participated in the previous games in Berlin 1936 but were absent in London 1948 were Bolivia, Bulgaria, Costa Rica, Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] In the case of the Baltic nations, they had been occupied and annexed by the Soviet Union, only returning to the games many decades later.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Bulgaria, Romania and Mandatory Palestine accepted invitations for the Games but withdrew a few days before it began.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Puerto Rico, an unincorporated territory and commonwealth of the United States, made its Olympic debut as an independent team.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] Bermuda, Jamaica, Trinidad and Tobago, Singapore and British Guyana were part of the British Empire.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1948 Summer Games, ranked by number of gold medals won.
[src:bbc-one/1948-summer-olympics] The host nation was 12th, with 27 medals, including four golds.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] The **2010 FIFA World Cup** was the 19th FIFA World Cup, the world championship for men's national football teams.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] It took place in South Africa from 11 June to 11 July 2010.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] The bidding process for hosting the tournament finals was open only to African nations.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] In 2004, the international football federation, FIFA, selected South Africa over Egypt and Morocco to become the first African nation to host the finals.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] The matches were played in 10 stadiums in nine host cities around the country, with the opening and final played at the Soccer City stadium in South Africa's largest city, Johannesburg.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Thirty-two teams were selected for participation via a worldwide qualification tournament that began in August 2007.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] In the first round of the tournament finals, the teams competed in round-robin groups of four teams for points, with the top two teams in each group proceeding.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] These 16 teams advanced to the knockout stage, where three rounds of play decided which teams would participate in the final.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] In the final, Spain, the European champions, beat third-time losing finalists the Netherlands 1–0 after extra time to win their first world title.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Spain became the eighth nation to win the tournament and the first European nation to win the World Cup outside its home continent: all previous World Cups held outside Europe had been won by South American nations.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] It was also the first time that the FIFA World Cup was passed between two different nations representing the same continent (as the previous cup holder had been Italy, who won the 2006 edition).
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Spain became the first national team to win the tournament after losing the first match at the finals and the first team since 1978 to win the World Cup after losing a game in the group stage.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] As a result of their win, Spain represented the World in the 2013 FIFA Confederations Cup.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Host nation South Africa were eliminated in the group stage, as were both 2006 World Cup finalists, Italy and France.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] It was the first time that the hosts had been eliminated in the group stage and the first of three successive World Cups that the defending champions would be eliminated in the group stage.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] New Zealand, with their three draws, were the only undefeated team in the tournament, but they were also eliminated in the group stage.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Africa was chosen as the host for the 2010 World Cup as part of a short-lived rotation policy, abandoned in 2007, to rotate the event among football confederations.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Five African nations placed bids to host the 2010 World Cup: Egypt, Morocco, South Africa and a joint bid from Libya and Tunisia.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Following the decision of the FIFA Executive Committee not to allow co-hosted tournaments, Tunisia withdrew from the bidding process.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] The committee also decided not to consider Libya's solo bid as it no longer met all the stipulations laid down in the official *List of Requirements*.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] The winning bid was announced by FIFA president Sepp Blatter at a media conference on 15 May 2004 in Zürich; in the first round of voting, South Africa received 14 votes, Morocco received 10 and Egypt no votes.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] South Africa, which had narrowly failed to win the right to host the 2006 event, was thus awarded the right to host the tournament.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Campaigning for South Africa to be granted host status, Nelson Mandela had previously spoken of the importance of football in his life, stating that while incarcerated in Robben Island prison playing football "made us feel alive and triumphant despite the situation we found ourselves in".
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] With South Africa winning their bid, an emotional Mandela raised the FIFA World Cup Trophy.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] During 2006 and 2007, rumours circulated in various news sources that the 2010 World Cup could be moved to another country.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Schmidt, and, reportedly, some FIFA executives expressed concern over the planning, organisation, and pace of South Africa's preparations.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] FIFA officials repeatedly expressed their confidence in South Africa as host, stating that a contingency plan existed only to cover natural catastrophes, as had been in place at previous FIFA World Cups.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] On 28 May 2015, media covering the 2015 FIFA corruption case reported that high-ranking officials from the South African bid committee had secured the right to host the World Cup by paying US$10 million in bribes to then-FIFA Vice President Jack Warner and to other FIFA Executive Committee members.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] On 4 June 2015, FIFA executive Chuck Blazer, having co-operated with the FBI and the Swiss authorities, confirmed that he and the other members of FIFA's executive committee were bribed in order to promote the South African 1998 and 2010 World Cup bids.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] On 6 June 2015, *The Daily Telegraph* reported that Morocco had actually won the vote, but South Africa was awarded the tournament instead.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] The qualification draw for the 2010 World Cup was held in Durban on 25 November 2007.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] As the host nation, South Africa qualified automatically for the tournament.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] As in the previous tournament, the defending champions were not given an automatic berth, and Italy had to participate in qualification.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] With a pool of entrants comprising 204 of the 208 FIFA national teams at the time, the 2010 World Cup shares with the 2008 Summer Olympics the record for most competing nations in a sporting event.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Serbia also made its first appearance as an independent nation, having previously been present as Kingdom of Yugoslavia in 1930, as SFR Yugoslavia from 1950 to 1990, as FR Yugoslavia in 1998 and as Serbia and Montenegro in 2006.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] The highest ranked team not to qualify was Croatia (ranked 10th), while the lowest ranked team that did qualify was North Korea (ranked 105th).
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] The following 32 teams, shown with final pre-tournament rankings, qualified for the final tournament.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Five new stadiums were built for the tournament, and five of the existing venues were upgraded.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Construction costs were expected to be R8.4 billion (just over US$1 billion or €950 million).
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] South Africa also improved its public transport infrastructure within the host cities, including Johannesburg's Gautrain and other metro systems, and major road networks were improved.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] In March 2009, Danny Jordaan, the president of the 2010 World Cup organising committee, reported that all stadiums for the tournament were on schedule to be completed within six months.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] The country implemented special measures to ensure the safety and security of spectators in accordance with standard FIFA requirements, including a temporary restriction of flight operation in the airspace surrounding the stadiums.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] At a ceremony to mark 100 days before the event, FIFA president Sepp Blatter praised the readiness of the country for the event.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] On 8 July 2009, 70,000 construction workers who were working on the new stadiums walked off their jobs.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] The majority of the workers receive R2500 per month (about £192, €224 or US$313), but the unions alleged that some workers were grossly underpaid.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] A spokesperson for the National Union of Mineworkers said to the SABC that the "no work no pay" strike would go on until FIFA assessed penalties on the organisers.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Other unions threatened to strike into 2011.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] The strike was swiftly resolved and workers were back at work within a week of it starting.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] There were no further strikes and all stadiums and construction projects were completed in time for the kick off.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] The total prize money on offer for the tournament was confirmed by FIFA as US$420 million (including payments of US$40 million to domestic clubs), a 60 percent increase on the 2006 tournament.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Before the tournament, each of the 32 entrants received US$1 million for preparation costs.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] In a first for the World Cup, FIFA made payments to the domestic clubs of the players representing their national teams at the tournament.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] This saw a total of US$40 million paid to domestic clubs.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] In 2005, the organisers released a provisional list of 12 venues to be used for the World Cup: Bloemfontein, Cape Town, Durban, Johannesburg (two venues), Kimberley, Klerksdorp, Nelspruit, Polokwane, Port Elizabeth, Pretoria, and Rustenburg.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] This was narrowed down to the ten venues that were officially announced by FIFA on 17 March 2006.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] The altitude of several venues affected the motion of the ball and player performance, although FIFA's medical chief downplayed this consideration.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Six of the ten venues were over 1,200 m (3,900 ft) above sea level, with the two Johannesburg venues—FNB Stadium (also known as Soccer City) and Ellis Park Stadium—the highest at approximately 1,750 m (5,740 ft).
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] FNB Stadium, Cape Town Stadium, and Nelson Mandela Bay Stadium in Port Elizabeth were the most-used venues, each hosting eight matches.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Ellis Park Stadium and Moses Mabhida Stadium in Durban hosted seven matches each, while Loftus Versfeld Stadium in Pretoria, Free State Stadium in Bloemfontein and Royal Bafokeng Stadium in Rustenburg hosted six matches each.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Peter Mokaba Stadium in Polokwane and Mbombela Stadium in Nelspruit hosted four matches each, but did not host any knockout-stage matches.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] The base camps were used by the 32 national squads to stay and train before and during the World Cup tournament.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] In February 2010, FIFA announced the base camps for each participating team.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Fifteen teams were in Gauteng Province, while six teams were based in KwaZulu-Natal, four in the Western Cape, three in North West Province, and one each in Mpumalanga, the Eastern Cape, and the Northern Cape.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] The FIFA Organising Committee approved the procedure for the final draw on 2 December 2009.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] The seeding was based on the October 2009 FIFA World Ranking and seven squads joined hosts South Africa as seeded teams for the final draw.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] No two teams from the same confederation were to be drawn in the same group, except allowing a maximum of two European teams in a group.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] The group draw was staged in Cape Town, South Africa, on 4 December 2009 at the Cape Town International Convention Centre.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] The ceremony was presented by South African actress Charlize Theron, assisted by FIFA Secretary General Jérôme Valcke.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] The balls were drawn by English football star David Beckham and African sporting figures Haile Gebrselassie, John Smit, Makhaya Ntini, Matthew Booth and Simphiwe Dludlu.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] FIFA's Referees' Committee selected 29 referees through its Refereeing Assistance Programme to officiate at the World Cup: four from the AFC, three from the CAF, six from CONMEBOL, four from CONCACAF, two from the OFC, and ten from UEFA.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] English referee Howard Webb was chosen to referee the final, making him the first person to referee both the UEFA Champions League final and the World Cup final in the same year.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] As with the 2006 tournament, each team's squad for the 2010 World Cup consisted of 23 players.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Each participating national association had to confirm their final 23-player squad by 1 June 2010.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Teams were permitted to make late replacements in the event of serious injury, at any time up to 24 hours before their first game.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Of the 736 players participating in the tournament, over half played their club football in five European domestic leagues; those in England (117 players), Germany (84), Italy (80), Spain (59) and France (46).
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] The English, German and Italian squads were made up of entirely home based players, while only Nigeria had no players from clubs in their own league.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] In all, players from 52 national leagues entered the tournament.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] FC Barcelona of Spain was the club contributing the most players to the tournament, with 13 players of their side travelling, 7 with the Spanish team, while another 7 clubs contributed 10 players or more.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] In another first for South Africa 2010, one squad included three siblings.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Jerry, Johnny, and Wilson Palacios made history thanks to their inclusion in Honduras's 23-man list.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Unusually, the game between Germany and Ghana had two brothers playing for opposite nations, with Jérôme Boateng and Kevin-Prince Boateng playing respectively.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] The tournament match schedule was announced in November 2007.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] In the first round, or group stage, the 32 teams were divided into eight groups of four, with each team playing the other three teams in their group once.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Teams were awarded three points for a win, one point for a draw and none for a defeat.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] The top two teams in each group advanced to the round of 16.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] The South American teams performed strongly, with all five advancing to the round of 16 (four as group winners), and four further advancing to the quarter-finals.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] However, only Uruguay advanced to the semi-finals.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Of the six African teams, only Ghana advanced to the round of 16.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] South Africa became the first host nation in World Cup history to be eliminated in the first round, despite beating France and drawing with Mexico, while Ghana and Ivory Coast were the only other African teams to win a match.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] The overall performance of the African teams, in the first World Cup to be hosted on the continent, was judged as disappointing by observers such as Cameroon great Roger Milla.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Only six out of the thirteen UEFA teams advanced to the round of 16, a record low since the introduction of this stage in 1986.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Nonetheless, the final was contested by two European teams.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] In another World Cup first, the two finalists from the preceding tournament, Italy and France, were eliminated at the group stage, with Italy becoming the third defending champions to be eliminated in the first round after Brazil in 1966 and France in 2002.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] New Zealand, one of the lowest-ranked teams, surprised many by drawing all three of their group matches, ending the tournament as the only undefeated team.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] The knockout stage comprised the 16 teams that advanced from the group stage of the tournament.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] There were four rounds of matches, with each round eliminating half of the teams entering that round.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] The successive rounds were the round of 16, quarter-finals, semi-finals, and the final.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] There was also a play-off to decide third and fourth place.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] For each game in the knockout stage, any draw at 90 minutes was followed by thirty minutes of extra time; if scores were still level, there was a penalty shoot-out to determine who progressed to the next round.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] In this round, each group winner (A to H) was paired against the runner-up from another group.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] FIFA President Sepp Blatter took the unusual step of apologising to England and Mexico for the decisions that went against them, saying: "Yesterday I spoke to the two federations directly concerned by referees' mistakes [...] I apologised to England and Mexico.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] The three quarter-finals between European and South American teams all resulted in wins for Europeans.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Germany had a 4–0 victory over Argentina, and the Netherlands came from behind to beat Brazil 2–1, handing the Brazilians their first loss in a World Cup match held outside Europe (other than in a penalty shoot-out) since 1950 when Uruguay won the decisive match 2–1.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Spain reached the final four for the first time since 1950 after a 1–0 win over Paraguay.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Uruguay, the only South American team to reach the semi-finals, overcame Ghana in a penalty shoot-out after a 1–1 draw in which Ghana missed a penalty at the end of extra time after Luis Suárez handled the ball on the line.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] The Netherlands qualified for the final for the third time with a 3–2 win over Uruguay.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Spain reached their first ever final with a 1–0 victory over Germany.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] As a result, it was the first World Cup final not to feature at least one of Brazil, Italy, Germany or Argentina.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] It also guaranteed that there would be a new World Cup champion, as neither Spain nor the Netherlands had won the tournament before.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Germany defeated Uruguay 3–2 to secure third place.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Germany holds the record for most third-place finishes in the World Cup (4), while Uruguay holds the record for most fourth-place finishes (3).
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] The final was held on 11 July 2010 at Soccer City, Johannesburg.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Spain defeated the Netherlands 1–0, with an extra time goal from Andrés Iniesta.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Iniesta scored the latest winning goal in a FIFA World Cup final (116th minute).
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] The win gave Spain their first World Cup title, becoming the eighth team to win it.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] This made them the first new winner without home advantage since Brazil in 1958, and the first team to win the tournament after having lost their opening game.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] A large number of fouls were committed in the final match.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Referee Howard Webb handed out 14 yellow cards, more than doubling the previous record for this fixture, set when Argentina and West Germany shared six cards in 1986, and John Heitinga of the Netherlands was sent off for receiving a second yellow card.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] The Netherlands had chances to score, most notably in the 60th minute when Arjen Robben was released by Wesley Sneijder to be one-on-one with Spain's goalkeeper Iker Casillas, only for Casillas to save the shot with an outstretched leg.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] For Spain, Sergio Ramos missed a free header from a corner kick when he was unmarked.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Iniesta finally broke the deadlock in extra time, scoring a volleyed shot from a pass by Cesc Fàbregas.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] This result marked the first time that two different teams from the same continent had won successive World Cups (following Italy in 2006), and saw Europe reaching 10 World Cup titles, surpassing South America's nine titles.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Spain became the first team since West Germany in 1974 to win the World Cup as European champions.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] The result also marked the first time that a European nation had won a World Cup that was not hosted on European soil.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] A closing ceremony was held before the final, featuring singer Shakira.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p01] Afterwards, the former South African President Nelson Mandela made a brief appearance on the pitch, wheeled in by a motorcart.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] South African winger Siphiwe Tshabalala was the first player to score a goal in the competition, in their 1–1 draw against Mexico, the opening game of the tournament.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] Danish defender Daniel Agger was credited with the first own goal of the tournament, in his side's 2–0 loss to the Netherlands.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] Argentine striker Gonzalo Higuaín was the only player to score a hat-trick in the tournament, in Argentina's 4–1 win over South Korea, the match where the second and last own goal was scored.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] It became the 49th World Cup hat-trick in the history of the tournament.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] Spain set a new record for the fewest goals scored by a World Cup-winning team, with eight.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] The previous record low was 11, set by Brazil in 1994, England in 1966, and Italy in 1938.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] Spain had the fewest goalscorers for a champion as well (three – Villa with five goals, Iniesta with two and Puyol with one).
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] They also had the fewest goals conceded for a champion (2), equal with Italy (2006) and France (1998).
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] Spain's victory marked the first time that a team won the World Cup without conceding a goal in the knockout stage.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] The four top scorers in the tournament had five goals each.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] All of the four top scorers also came from the teams that finished in the top four, Spain, the Netherlands, Germany, and Uruguay.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] The Golden Boot went to Thomas Müller of Germany who had three assists, compared to one for the three others.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] The Silver Boot went to David Villa of Spain, who played a total of 635 minutes, and the Bronze Boot to Wesley Sneijder of the Netherlands, who played 652 minutes.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] Diego Forlán of Uruguay had five goals and one assist in 654 minutes.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] A further three players scored four goals.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] Only 145 goals were scored at South Africa 2010, the lowest of any FIFA World Cup since the tournament switched to a 64-game format.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] This continued a downward trend since the first 64-game finals were held 12 years earlier, with 171 goals at France 1998, 161 at Korea/Japan 2002 and 147 at Germany 2006.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] Shortly after the final, FIFA issued a final ranking of every team in the tournament.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] The ranking was based on progress in the competition, overall results and quality of the opposition.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] All 32 teams are ranked based on criteria which have been used by FIFA.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] FIFA released an All-Star Team based on the Castrol performance index in its official website.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] For the first time, FIFA published a Dream Team decided by an online public vote.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] People were invited to select a team (in a 4–4–2 formation) and best coach; voting was open until 23:59 on 11 July 2010, with entrants going into a draw to win a prize.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] Six of the eleven players came from the Spanish team, as did the coach.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] The remainder of the team comprised two players from Germany, and one each from Brazil, the Netherlands and Uruguay.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] The sponsors of the 2010 World Cup are divided into three categories: FIFA Partners, FIFA World Cup Sponsors and National Supporters.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] The 2010 finals amplified international public awareness of the vuvuzela, a long horn blown by fans throughout matches.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] Many World Cup competitors complained about the noise caused by the vuvuzela horns, including France's Patrice Evra, who blamed the horns for the team's poor performance.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] Other critics include Lionel Messi, who complained that the sound of the vuvuzelas hampered communication among players on the pitch, and broadcasting companies, which complained that commentators' voices were drowned out by the sound.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] Others watching on television complained that the ambient audio feed from the stadium contained only the sounds of the vuvuzelas with the usual sounds of people in the stands drowned out.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] A spokesperson for ESPN and other networks said that they were taking steps to minimise the ambient noise on their broadcasts.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] The BBC also investigated the possibility of offering broadcasts without vuvuzela noise.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] The official mascot for the 2010 World Cup was *Zakumi*, an anthropomorphised African leopard with green hair, presented on 22 September 2008.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] His name came from "ZA" (the international abbreviation for South Africa) and the term *kumi*, which means "ten" in various African languages.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] The mascot's colours reflected those of the host nation's playing strip – yellow and green.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] The match ball for the 2010 World Cup, manufactured by Adidas, was named the *Jabulani*, which means *"bringing joy to everyone"* in Zulu.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] It was the 11th World Cup match ball made by the German sports equipment maker; it featured 11 colours, representing each player of a team on the pitch and the 11 official languages of South Africa.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] A special match ball with gold panels, called the *Jo'bulani*, was used at the final in Johannesburg.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] The ball was constructed using a new design, consisting of eight thermally bonded, three-dimensional panels.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] These were spherically moulded from ethylene-vinyl acetate (EVA) and thermoplastic polyurethanes (TPU).
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] The surface of the ball was textured with grooves, a technology developed by Adidas called GripnGroove that was intended to improve the ball's aerodynamics.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] The design received considerable academic input, being developed in partnership with researchers from Loughborough University, United Kingdom.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] The balls were made in China, using latex bladders made in India, thermoplastic polyurethane-elastomer from Taiwan, ethylene vinyl acetate, isotropic polyester/cotton fabric, and glue and ink from China.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] Some football stars complained about the new ball, arguing that its movements were difficult to predict.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] Brazilian goalkeeper Júlio César compared it to a "supermarket" ball that favored strikers and worked against goalkeepers.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] Argentinian coach Diego Maradona said: "We won't see any long passes in this World Cup because the ball doesn't fly straight." However, a number of Adidas-sponsored players responded favourably to the ball.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] The official song of the 2010 World Cup "Waka Waka (This Time for Africa)", was performed by the Colombian singer Shakira and the band Freshlyground from South Africa, and is sung in both English and Spanish.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] The song is based on a traditional African soldiers' song, "Zangalewa".
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] Shakira and Freshlyground performed the song at the pre-tournament concert in Soweto on 10 June.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] It was also sung at the opening ceremony on 11 June and at the closing ceremony on 11 July.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] The official mascot song of the 2010 World Cup was "Game On".
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] The official anthem of the 2010 World Cup was "Sign of a Victory" by R.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] Kelly with the Soweto Spiritual Singers, which was also performed at the opening ceremony.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] Tournament organiser Danny Jordaan dismissed concerns that the attack on the Togo national team which took place in Angola in January 2010 had any relevance to the security arrangements for the World Cup.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] There were also reports of thefts against visitors to the country for the World Cup.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] Tourists from China, Portugal, Spain, South Korea, Japan and Colombia had become victims of crime.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] On 19 June after the match between England and Algeria, a fan was able to break through the FIFA-appointed security staff at Green Point stadium and gain access to the England team dressing room.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] The breach took place shortly after Prince William and Prince Harry had left the room.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] The trespasser was then released before he could be handed over to the Police.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] The Football Association lodged a formal complaint with FIFA and demanded that security be increased.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] As with many "hallmark events" throughout the world, the 2010 FIFA World Cup has been connected to evictions, which many claim are meant to 'beautify the city', impress visiting tourists, and hide shackdwellers.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] NGOs, international human rights organisations, and the Anti-Eviction Campaign have publicly criticised the conditions in Blikkiesdorp and said that the camp has been used to accommodate poor families evicted to make way for the 2010 World Cup.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] However some have argued that evictions are ordinarily common in South Africa and that in the lead up to the tournament many evictions were erroneously ascribed to the World Cup.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] Some groups experienced complications in regards to scheduled sporting events, advertising, or broadcasting, as FIFA attempted to maximise control of media rights during the Cup.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] Affected parties included an international rugby union Test match, a South African airline and some TV networks, all of whom were involved in various legal struggles with World Cup organisers.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] During the tournament, group ticket-holders who did not utilise all their allotted tickets led to some early-round matches having as many as 11,000 unoccupied seats.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] While the event did help to boost the image of South Africa, it turned out to be a major financial disappointment.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] Construction costs for venues and infrastructure amounted to £3 billion (€3.6 billion), and the government expected that increased tourism would help to offset these costs to the amount of £570 million (€680 million).
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] However, only £323 million (€385 million) were actually taken in as 309,000 foreign fans came to South Africa, well below the expected number of 450,000.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] Local vendors were prohibited from selling food and merchandise within a 1.5 kilometre radius of any stadium hosting a World Cup match.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] For a vendor to operate within the radius, a registration fee of R60,000 (approximately US$7,888 or €6,200) had to be paid to FIFA.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] This fee was out of most local vendors' reach, as they are simple one-man-operated vendors.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] This prevented international visitors from experiencing local South African food.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] Some local vendors felt cheated out of an opportunity for financial gain and spreading South African culture in favour of multinational corporations.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] FIFA president Sepp Blatter declared the event "a huge financial success for everybody, for Africa, for South Africa and for FIFA," with revenue to FIFA of £2.24 billion (€2 billion).
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] In a December 2010 *Quality Progress*, FIFA President Blatter rated South Africa's organisational efforts a nine out of 10 scale, declaring that South Africa could be considered a plan B for all future competitions.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] The South African Quality Institute (SAQI) assisted in facility construction, event promotion, and organisations.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] The main issue listed in the article was lack of sufficient public transportation.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] The 2010 FIFA World Cup was expected to be the most-watched television event in history.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] Hundreds of broadcasters, representing about 70 countries, transmitted the Cup to a TV audience that FIFA officials expect to exceed a cumulative 26 billion people, an average of approximately 400 million viewers per match.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] FIFA estimated that around 700 million viewers would watch the World Cup final.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] New forms of digital media have also allowed viewers to watch coverage through alternative means.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] "With games airing live on cell phones and computers, the World Cup will get more online coverage than any major sporting event yet," said Jake Coyle of the Associated Press.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] In the United States, ABC, ESPN, and ESPN2 averaged a 2.1 rating, 2,288,000 households and 3,261,000 viewers for the 64 World Cup games.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] The rating was up 31 percent from a 1.6 in 2006, while households increased 32 percent from 1,735,000 and viewers rose from 2,316,000.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] The increases had been higher while the US remained in the tournament.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] Through the first 50 games, the rating was up 48 percent, households increased 54 percent and viewers rose 60 percent.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] Univision averaged 2,624,000 viewers for the tournament, up 17 percent, and 1,625,000 households, an increase of 11 percent.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] An executive of the Nielsen Company, a leading audience research firm in the US, described the aggregate numbers for both networks' coverage of the match between the United States and Ghana as "phenomenal".
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] Live World Cup streaming on ESPN3.com pulled in some of the largest audiences in history, as 7.4 million unique viewers tuned in for matches.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] In total, ESPN3.com generated 942 million minutes of viewing or more than two hours per unique viewer.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] All 64 live matches were viewed by an average of 114,000 persons per minute.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] Most impressive were the numbers for the semi-final between Spain and Germany, which was viewed by 355,000 people per minute, making it ESPN3.com's largest average audience ever.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] Sony technology was used to film the tournament.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] 25 of the matches were captured using 3D cameras.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] Footage was captured in 3D through Sony's proprietary multi-image MPE-200 processors, housed in specially designed 3D outside broadcast trucks.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] It supplied its flagship HDC-1500 cameras as well as its new HDC-P1 unit, a compact, point-of-view (POV)-type camera with 3, 2/3-inch CCD sensors.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] The 3D games were produced for FIFA by Host Broadcast Services.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] In PlayStation Home, Sony released a virtual space based on the 2010 FIFA World Cup in the Japanese version of Home on 3 December 2009.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] This virtual space is called the "FevaArena" and is a virtual stadium of the 2010 FIFA World Cup, featuring different areas for events, a FIFA mini-game, and a shop with FIFA related content.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] On 27 April 2010, EA Sports released the official 2010 World Cup video game.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] FIFA expanded the FIFA Fan Fest, hosting in Sydney, Buenos Aires, Berlin, Paris, Rome, Rio de Janeiro, and Mexico City, as well as several venues around South Africa.
[src:bbc-one/2010-fifa-world-cup-p02] The Durban Fan Fest was the most popular in South Africa during the tournament followed by the Cape Town Fan Fest.
[src:bbc-one/3-mills-studios] In August 2004, the London Development Agency (LDA) acquired 3 Mills Studios.
[src:bbc-one/3-mills-studios] As parent organisation of the *Creative London* agency, the LDA's role included supporting business and skills, researching industry needs, and promoting London for film-making.
[src:bbc-one/3-mills-studios] The site is now one of London's most important film and television studios.
[src:bbc-one/3-mills-studios] Ownership transferred to the London Legacy Development Corporation in 2010 which is the organisation responsible for planning, developing, and managing the Olympic Park after the 2012 Summer Olympics.
[src:bbc-one/3-mills-studios] 3 Mills Studios has over 75,000 sq ft (7,000 m2) of filming space, including 11 filming stages and nine rehearsal rooms.
[src:bbc-one/3-mills-studios] Stage 5 at 10,437 sq ft (969.6 m2) has a similar floor size to the Royal Albert Hall.
[src:bbc-one/3-mills-studios] There are nine rehearsal rooms on site: Rehearsal Room 6 at 2,507 sq ft (232.9 m2) is the largest and Rehearsal Room 3 at 280.9 sq ft (26.10 m2) is the smallest.
[src:bbc-one/3-mills-studios] 3 Mills Studios has a large range of ancillary spaces including; production offices, props workshops, five prop stores ranging from 712 to 1,319 sq ft (66.1 to 122.5 m2), make-up rooms, and dressing rooms.
[src:bbc-one/3-mills-studios] Many feature films have been made at 3 Mills Studios, including *Legend*, *Topsy-Turvy*, *Sexy Beast*, *Eastern Promises*, *Attack the Block*, *Berberian Sound Studio*, *Ill Manors*, *Powder Room*, *Made in Dagenham*, *Never Let Me Go*, *Farming* and *Lock, Stock and Two Smoking Barrels*.
[src:bbc-one/3-mills-studios] 3 Mills Studios' main focus has been on television shows.
[src:bbc-one/3-mills-studios] 3 Mills Studios has been home to BBC's *MasterChef* since 2014.
[src:bbc-one/3-mills-studios] 3 Mills was home to Channel 4's *Big Brother* for the first and second series along with the first series of *Celebrity Big Brother*.
[src:bbc-one/3-mills-studios] Other clients include Matthew Bourne's New Adventures, English National Opera, Raymond Gubbay Limited, Shakespeare's Globe and English National Ballet, as well as advertisers for Versace, Audi, Waitrose, Nissan, Gillette, Samsung, Gucci, Topshop, B&Q and Adidas.
[src:bbc-one/3-mills-studios] 3 Mills Studios also housed many rehearsals for the opening and closing ceremonies of the 2012 Summer Olympics.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] The **405-line** monochrome analogue television broadcasting system was the first fully electronic television system to be used in regular broadcasting.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] The number of television lines influences the image resolution, or quality of the picture.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] It was introduced with the BBC Television Service in 1936, suspended for the duration of World War II, and remained in operation in the UK until 1985.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] It was also used between 1961 and 1982 in Ireland, as well as from 1957 to 1973 for the Rediffusion Television cable service in Hong Kong.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] 405-line was approved as **System A** in the CCIR assignment of broadcast systems.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] Sometimes called the **Marconi-EMI system**, it was developed in 1934 by the EMI Research Team led by Isaac Shoenberg.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] The figure of 405 lines had been chosen following discussions over Sunday lunch at the home of Alan Blumlein.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] The system used interlacing; EMI had been experimenting with a 243-line all-electronic interlaced system since 1933.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] In the 405 system the scanning lines were broadcast in two complementary fields, 50 times per second, creating 25 frames per second.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] The actual image was 376 lines high and interlaced, with additional unused lines making the frame up to 405 lines to give the slow circuitry time to prepare for the next frame; in modern terms it would be described as *"376i"*.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] At the time of its introduction the 405-line system was referred to as *"high definition"* – which it was, compared to earlier systems, although of lower definition than 625-line and later standards.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] In the United States, the FCC had briefly approved a 405-line color television standard in October 1950, which was developed by CBS.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] The CBS system was incompatible with existing black-and-white receivers.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] It used a rotating color wheel, reduced the number of scan lines from 525 to 405, and increased the field rate from 60 to 144, but had an effective frame rate of only 24 frames per second.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] In 1934, the British government set up a committee (the "Television Committee") to advise on the future of TV broadcasting.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] The committee recommended that a "high definition" service (defined by them as being a system of 240 lines or more) should be run and established by the BBC.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] The recommendation was accepted and tenders were sought from industry.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] Two tenders were received: one from the Baird company offering a 240-line mechanical system, and the other from EMI offering a 405-line all-electronic one.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] The Television Committee advised that they were unable to choose between the two systems and that both tenders should be accepted, the two systems to be run together for an experimental period.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] This became the standard for all British TV broadcasts until the 1960s.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] It soon became apparent that television reception was also possible well outside the original intended service area.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] In February 1938, engineers at the RCA Research Station, Riverhead, Long Island, New York, in the US, were able to receive the BBC signal 5,000 km (3,100 mi) away, due to the signal being "bounced" back to earth from the ionosphere.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] A few minutes of programming were recorded on 16mm movie film.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] This is now considered to be the only surviving example of pre-war live British television.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] The images recorded included two of the original three BBC announcers, Jasmine Bligh and (in a brief shot) Elizabeth Cowell, an excerpt from an unknown period costume drama, and the BBC's station identification transmitted at the beginning and end of the day's programmes.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] The BBC temporarily ceased transmissions on 1 September 1939, the day of the German invasion of Poland, for the outbreak of World War II was imminent.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] After the BBC Television Service recommenced in 1946, distant reception reports were received from various parts of the world, including Italy, South Africa, India, the Middle East, North America and the Caribbean.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] The BBC lost its monopoly of the British television market in 1954, and the following year the commercial network ITV, comprising a consortium of regional companies, was launched.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] The subcarrier frequency was 2.6578125 MHz (525/2 times line frequency) with an "I" signal bandwidth of 500 kHz and a "Q" signal bandwidth of 300 kHz.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] Tests with PAL, SECAM and other NTSC subcarrier frequencies were also attempted.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] Some of these broadcasts were on UHF (also an experimental technology at the time), while others were carried over the regular VHF network outside of normal broadcasting hours.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] In 1964, the BBC launched its BBC2 service on UHF using only a 625-line system, which older sets could not receive.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] For several years BBC1 and ITV transmitted using the 405-line and BBC2 with the 625-line standard; the only way to receive them all was to use a complex "dual-standard" 405- and 625-line, VHF and UHF, receiver.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] The introduction of colour on BBC2 in 1967 necessitated an even more complex dual-standard set to receive all three channels with BBC2 in colour.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] Over time in 1968 and 1969, the different ITV regional channels and BBC1 switched over to broadcasting on the 625-line as well as the 405-line, a process which once completed meant that only 625-lines were necessary to receive all channels, with dual standard receivers no longer necessary.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] In November 1969, BBC1 and ITV started broadcasting in 625-line PAL colour on UHF.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] Their programming was now entirely produced using the new 625-line standard, and thus the 405-line broadcasts served only as a rebroadcast in monochrome for people who did not have the newer receivers and who could only receive BBC1 and ITV.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] This situation continued up to 3–4 January 1985, with 405-line VHF receivers only being able to pick up BBC1 and ITV regionals, and in monochrome only, while 625-line UHF receivers could also receive BBC2 and Channel 4/S4C in addition to BBC1 and ITV, and in either colour or monochrome.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] One reason for the long switchover period was the difficulty in matching the coverage level of the new UHF 625-line service with the very high level of geographic coverage achieved with the 405-line VHF service.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] The last 405-line transmissions were seen on 4 January 1985 in Scotland; they had been officially shut down one day earlier in the rest of the UK (although they were actually switched off at various points the next day).
[src:bbc-one/405-line] This left only the UHF PAL system in operation in the UK.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] The frequencies used by the 405-line system were initially left empty, but were later sold off; they are now used for other purposes, including DAB and trunked PMR commercial two-way radio systems.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] Ireland's use of the 405-line system began in 1961 (officially 31st of December 1961), with the launch of Telefís Éireann, but only extended to two main transmitters and their five relays, serving the east and north of the country.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] This was because many people in these areas already had 405-line sets for receiving UK broadcasts from Wales or Northern Ireland.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] Telefís Éireann's primary standard was 625-line; it began using this in the summer of 1962, more than two years before the UK had any 625-line channels.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] The last 405 line transmitters in the UK and Ireland were shut down in 1985.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] The last 405-line relays, in County Donegal, were turned off in 1982; the main transmitters had been shut down in 1978 to free up frequencies for RTÉ 2, and after then the relays had been fed by standards converters from the local 625-line transmitter.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] For the last five years of RTÉ's 405-line simulcasting, a simple orthicon converter was used, essentially a 405-line camera pointed at a 625-line monitor, as the more expensive system converters that RTÉ had previously used were now inoperable.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] The 405-line system was used in the Rediffusion Television cable television service in Hong Kong, established in 1957, making it both the first British colony and the first predominantly Chinese city to have television.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] The service of 405-line system ended in 1973, replaced by 625-line PAL system free-to-air broadcast.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] For a brief time in 1939 there were experimental 405-line transmissions from stations in Montrouge in France and Eindhoven in the Netherlands, Czechoslovakia and Switzerland.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] After the U.S. adopted the NTSC 525-line monochrome standard for commercial broadcasting in 1941, subsequent efforts were made to upgrade the standard so that it could also accommodate a "compatible" colour broadcasting system.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] This system was a field-sequential colour system which electronically transmitted a 405 lines, 144 fields per second monochrome picture.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] Colour was provided mechanically by means of a synchronized rotating transparent Red-Green-Blue disk, which was placed in front of the receiver screen.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] Regular broadcast channels were used to transmit the 405-line system signals, but the millions of existing NTSC 525-line television receivers could only correctly process the audio portion of these transmissions, so unless these sets were modified they would only display a jumbled picture.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] CBS aired a variety show special entitled *Premiere* on 25 June 1951 to officially launch commercial 405-line colour broadcasting, but just four months later CBS ended its colour broadcasts.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] CBS's efforts were hindered from the beginning by a widespread lack of acceptance, and the ultimate setback came at the end of the year when the U.S. government temporarily banned the manufacture of colour televisions, ostensibly to conserve resources during the Korean War.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] In 1953, the FCC rescinded its approval of the CBS 405-line colour system.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] In its place it approved a newly improved and now satisfactory second NTSC 525-line standard which had been developed by RCA.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] It provided for colour broadcasting yet remained compatible with existing 525-line monochrome sets.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] 405-line is System A in the CCIR assignment of broadcast systems.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] The audio uses amplitude modulation rather than the frequency modulation in use on modern analogue systems.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] In addition, the system was broadcast in an aspect ratio of 5:4 until 3 April 1950, when it changed to the more common 4:3 format.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] All System A transmitters used vestigial sideband transmission, with the single exception of Alexandra Palace in London, which closed down in 1957 when it was replaced by Crystal Palace.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] Secondly, the smoothing (filtering) of power supply circuits in early TV receivers was rather poor, and ripple superimposed on the DC could cause visual interference.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] However, the main problem was the susceptibility of the electron beam in the CRT being deflected by stray magnetic fields from nearby transformers or motors.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] If the picture was locked to the mains frequency, this interference would at least be static on the screen and thus relatively unnoticeable.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] The very earliest TV sets used a mains transformer; care had to be taken in design to prevent the transformer's stray magnetic field from disturbing the electron beam in the CRT.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] An interlaced system requires accurate positioning of scanning lines so the horizontal and vertical timebase must be in a precise ratio.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] This is done by passing the one through a series of electronic divider circuits to produce the other.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] Therefore, there has to be a straightforward mathematical relationship between the line and field frequencies, the latter being derived by dividing down from the former.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] The technology constraints of the 1930s meant that this division process could only be done using small integers, preferably no greater than 7, for good stability.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] The number of lines was odd because of 2:1 interlace.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] The 405-line system used a vertical frequency of 50 Hz (standard AC mains supply frequency in Britain) and a horizontal one of 10,125 Hz (50 × 405 ÷ 2 or, using the frame rate, 25 x 405), with 405 being derived from (3 × 3 × 3 × 3 × 5).
[src:bbc-one/405-line] A few 405-line videotapes still survive.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] However, the majority of surviving 405-line programmes are in the form of black and white film telerecordings, usually with optical soundtracks.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] Occasionally video re-recording would be employed instead, with a 625-line camera pointing at a 405-line monitor.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] This preserves the original 50-field interlaced format, but with some geometrical distortions owing to the curvature of the CRT monitors used at the time.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] 405-line programming may be recorded and played on an unmodified VHS or Betamax video recorder, as long as the input to the recorder is baseband rather than RF.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] Thus, various modern video recordings of 405-line programming also exist.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] Betamax was sometimes preferred for this, as the dropout compensator could be switched off on certain models for use with PCM digital audio decoders.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] When used with vestigial sideband filtering, the total bandwidth of a 405-line TV channel is 5 MHz, significantly less than the 8 MHz required by the 625-line System I, which replaced it in Britain.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] Systems in other countries used anything between six and fourteen megahertz of bandwidth per channel.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] The use of VHF frequencies combined with the narrow vision bandwidth — AM signals (at VHF low band frequencies) are less affected by noise as bandwidth is reduced — meant that 405-line signals could be received well even under marginal conditions.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] Therefore, it was possible to cover virtually all of the UK with a relatively small number of transmitting stations.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] The use of AM (rather than FM) for sound and the use of positive (rather than negative) video modulation made 405-line signals very prone to audible and visible impulse interference, such as that generated by the ignition systems of vehicles.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] Such interference manifested itself as a loud popping on sound and large bright spots on the picture, which viewers found much more noticeable than the dark spots encountered when such interference is encountered on a signal using negative video modulation.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] With positive modulation, interference could easily be of similar amplitude to the sync pulses (which were represented by 0–30% of the transmitter output).
[src:bbc-one/405-line] The early time-base circuits were less able to discriminate between the signals and the picture would break up.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] By contrast, in negative modulation sync, pulses represent peak transmitter output (70–100% output).
[src:bbc-one/405-line] As a result, impulse interference would cause visual dark spots before it was large enough to affect the synchronisation of the picture.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] If the interference was large enough, the picture was probably unwatchable anyway.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] The later introduction of flywheel sync circuits rendered the picture much more stable, but these could not have alleviated some of the problems with positive modulation.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] Almost all television systems that succeeded the 405-line system adopted negative modulation for this reason alone.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] First-generation AGC merely detected the average value of the transmitted signal; however, due to the positively modulated carrier, peak power represented peak white – not guaranteed to be present.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] Thus for a completely black picture, the AGC circuit would increase the RF gain to restore the average carrier amplitude.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] The result was a screen that was not black but mid-grey.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] In fact, the total light output of early TV sets was practically constant regardless of the picture content.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] By the mid-1950s, several manufacturers started to introduce gated-AGC systems to avoid this issue.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] A delayed pulse was derived from the recovered line-sync signal.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] This pulse would trigger a gate which would sample the received video signal during the "back porch" which was a guaranteed black-level transmitted between the end of the line-sync pulse and the start of the picture information.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] The introduction of negative modulation in later systems simplified the problem because peak carrier power represented sync pulses (which were always guaranteed to be present).
[src:bbc-one/405-line] A simple peak-detector AGC circuit would detect the amplitude of only the sync pulses, thus measuring the strength of the received signal.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] The 405-line system produced a noticeable 10.125 kHz whistle in many sets, equal to the number of lines per second.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] This high-pitched whistle was caused by magnetostriction in the line output transformer.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] This is a common artifact in sets that use a cathode-ray tube.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] While all CRT-based television systems produce such a noise, the higher number of lines per second in later standards produces frequencies (PAL's 15.625 kHz and NTSC's 15.734 kHz) that are at the upper end of the audible spectrum, which not all people are able to hear.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] Modern sets using plasma, LCD or OLED display technology are completely free of this effect as they are composed of a million or more individually controllable elements, rather than using a single magnetically deflected beam, so there is no requirement to generate the scanning signal.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] The question was raised again from time to time, but a series of tests, conducted during 1952 in cooperation with the British Radio Equipment Manufacturers' Association, confirmed that there was no general need for equalizing pulses.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] On some larger TV screen sizes, the scanned lines were not fat enough to give 100% coverage of the CRT.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] The result was a lined picture with darkness between each horizontal scanned line, reducing picture brightness and contrast.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] Larger screen sets often used a spot wobble oscillator, that slightly elongated the scanning spot vertically at high frequency to avoid this line separation effect without reducing horizontal sharpness.
[src:bbc-one/405-line] Spot wobble was also utilised when making telerecordings of 405-line programmes.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] Croft and Lloyd devised the concept as a parody of BBC wartime drama *Secret Army* and initially launched the programme with a pilot on 30 December 1982.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] The sitcom was eventually commissioned following the success of the pilot and ran for nine series between 7 September 1984 until its conclusion on 14 December 1992.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] Both Lloyd and Croft wrote the scripts for the first six series, while the remainder were handled by Lloyd and Paul Adam.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] Much like previous sitcoms created by Croft and Lloyd, the programme employed notable elements such as memorable catchphrases and ending credits, cultural clichés, physical humour and visual gags.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] However, *'Allo 'Allo!* differed from these other sitcoms by featuring overarching plot lines rather than simple stand-alone stories, as well as the device of having actors speaking English but with theatrical foreign accents to distinguish each character's nationality.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] The sitcom gained strong ratings during its run, with its success leading to it receiving stage show reproductions.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] A special entitled *The Return of 'Allo 'Allo!*, aired on 22 March 2007, featured cast members returning to reprise their original roles to perform in a special story after the conclusion of the programme.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] It was accompanied by a documentary about the sitcom, including a highlight reel of episodes and interviews with the cast, production team and fans.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] Throughout the programme's broadcast, the sitcom features a number of overarching storylines, with two of these being the most conspicuous.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] René is notably forced into handling the stolen painting under threat of execution, but also due to being indebted to von Strohm for allowing him to fake his death when he is sentenced to execution for unjustified accusations of aiding the Resistance in an act of sabotage.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] The painting itself is at one point lost during its concealment, and when it is found a copy is forged.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] It is also sought not only by von Strohm but also Herr Flick who, rather than return it to Berlin, intends to keep it for himself.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] The second storyline concerns the involvement of two stranded British airmen, shot down while over Nouvion.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] The schemes devised are so bizarre and complicated that they backfire, and usually collide with other schemes concocted by both von Strohm and the Gestapo, invariably leaving all three groups worse off than before.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] Other storylines include the efforts to remove von Klinkerhoffen's replacement from power, sabotaging the Germans' plan to invade England, and the subsequent build-up of German concern about an Allied invasion of France following the defeat of Italy.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] Like most characters devised for previous sitcoms, the cast for the programme were designed with notable elements to distinguish them throughout the series, be it a catchphrase, gimmick, or saying.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] As each episode builds on previous ones, viewers are often required to have followed the series to the episode they have reached in order to understand the plot.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] As *'Allo 'Allo!* revolved around individual story arcs spread across several episodes, the creators opted for using a comical version of the "As you remember ..." device, commonly used in serials, to act as a recap of events in the current story for the beginning of a new episode.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] This plot device was rare for comedy (including comedy animation), where plots are prominently gag-driven and self-contained, but its use in *'Allo 'Allo!* had a major impact on audiences connecting with the characters.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] It also had considerable benefits for re-runs, as it allowed local TV stations who had reshuffled episodes for their schedule to ensure that their audiences could be aware of the plot events surrounding the story of the episode being broadcast.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] The main characters of the series were of four nationalities – French, German, English and Italian.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] Lloyd and Croft portrayed this by having non-English characters speak English with the accent of the foreign language, while the English characters spoke in upper-class English accents.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] French, German and Italian characters could understand each other when speaking, but the English characters could not understand the others without someone "translating" for them and vice versa.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] The police officer Crabtree was introduced in the second series.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] Because the character was an undercover Englishman with a poor grasp of French, the actor, Arthur Bostrom, spoke perfectly when the character spoke in English, but extensively deployed malapropisms to represent when the character was speaking in French.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] Bostrom altered certain words in his sentences, substituting different vowels or consonants, changing them into different or nonsensical words, usually laden with innuendo.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] There were sustained attempts by the occupiers to appropriate the *Fallen Madonna*, a local treasure, to provide a nest egg after the war.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] The painting was seen and hidden in various guises; it was often secreted, with suggestive possibilities, in a long *knackwurst* sausage.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] An incredible number of forgeries of the *Fallen Madonna* were made, mostly by Lieutenant Gruber and Monsieur Leclerc, which were hidden in *knackwurst* sausages in René's kitchen.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] The forgeries were subsequently destroyed in various ways (burned, blown up, minced, eaten by a dog, etc.).
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] In the end of the *'Allo 'Allo!* series the Fallen Madonna is found long after the war by an elderly René; he and his mistress Yvette quickly elope to Spain with the painting to live happily ever after.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] Having previously sold for £4,000 in 2007, the original prop portrait from the series (*The Fallen Madonna with the Big Boobies)* sold for £15,000 at East Bristol Auctions in December 2018.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] The picture was purchased by a buyer in Nouvion.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] The BBC presented the 6th Marquess of Bath with a specially commissioned copy of the prop that was hung alongside Old Masters in Lord Bath's ancestral home, Longleat.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] After the pilot aired in December 1982, a full-length first series of seven episodes was commissioned and aired from September 1984 onwards.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] Series two, three and four followed annually, with six episodes each.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] Series five was commissioned with a view to syndicating the show in America.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] As a result, it aired as a single long series of twenty-six episodes between September 1988 and February 1989, with each episode running only twenty-five minutes to allow for commercials.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] The attempts to air the show in America failed (although screening rights to the series were later sold to PBS), and so series six had only eight episodes commissioned, which aired from September 1989 onwards.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] On 25 January 1990, Gorden Kaye suffered serious head injuries in a car crash brought on by gale-force winds.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] This delayed the start of the seventh series, which consisted of ten episodes airing from January 1991 onwards.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] Series 8 (7 episodes) followed in January 1992, and the ninth and final series of six episodes aired later that year from November onwards.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] The first was a 45-minute episode, which followed Series 2 in 1985, and the second was also a 45-minute episode, screened at Christmas 1991, preceding Series 8.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] In 1994, two years after the series ended, the BBC broadcast *The Best of 'Allo 'Allo!*, a compilation of clips from the series, linked by new scenes featuring Gorden Kaye and Carmen Silvera, in which René and Edith reminisce about the events of the war.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] On 22 March 2007, a one-off special episode entitled *The Return of 'Allo 'Allo!* was filmed in Manchester, and was broadcast on 28 April 2007 at 9 pm on BBC 2.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] The storyline involves René writing his memoirs after the war, and the events from the final episode in 1992 have been overlooked.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] The new scenes were interspersed with clips from the original series and new interviews.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] The actors who reprised their roles were: Gorden Kaye, Vicki Michelle, Sue Hodge, Kirsten Cooke, Arthur Bostrom, Guy Siner, Robin Parkinson, John D.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] In addition, Richard Gibson and Sam Kelly are interviewed, although they are not reprising their respective roles.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] The only main characters who did not appear in the reunion at all (barring those cases where the actor or actress had died) were Private Helga Geerhart (played by Kim Hartman) and Herr Engelbert von Smallhausen (played by John Louis Mansi).
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] In 2022, Channel 5 aired a 67-minute special retrospective for their "Comedy Classics" series.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] Cast, crew and celebrities discuss and pay tribute to the show.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] The documentary features interviews with Guy Siner, Vicki Michelle, Kim Hartman and Sue Hodge, as well as a previously unseen archive interview with Gorden Kaye.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] On 10 March 2008, ProSieben Sat.1 Media bought the rights to broadcast the series for the first time in Germany, which was broadcast on Sat.1 Comedy beginning on 15 February 2010.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] In the meantime, the series was also broadcast on German free TV on Comedy Central Germany .
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] Many storylines for *'Allo 'Allo* also derive directly from episodes of *Secret Army*, such as the valuable paintings and the accompanying forgeries, which both the Germans and the Resistance are seeking to obtain in the *Secret Army* second series episode "Weekend".
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] Some actors from *Secret Army* also appear in *''Allo 'Allo!*: Richard Marner, Guy Siner, John D.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] Collins, Hilary Minster, David Beckett and Louis Sheldon.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] Inspiration was also drawn from patriotic black-and-white British melodramas of the 1940s.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] The French village setting is reminiscent of 1972's *Clochemerle*, whilst René's intermediary role between the Germans and the Resistance reflects a comic version of Rick from *Casablanca* (as well as directly matching the proprietor of the café in *Secret Army*).
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] Having a café-cabaret in the plot, music was often performed on the show.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] This usually took place with Madame Edith singing, and either Lt.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] Gruber or Leclerc at the piano, played (out of vision) by Roy Moore.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] Occasionally, characters could also be seen whistling or humming tunes at certain points.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] David Croft and Roy Moore composed the theme tune performed at the start and end of each episode.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] It features a French-style melody performed on an accordion, accompanied by a string quartet and other instruments, in the **3** **4** (waltz) time signature.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] Carmen Silvera sang the full song and it was released on LP in the 1980s.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] The café cabaret music usually took the form of 1930s film and show tunes – reminiscent of the way period songs were also used in *Secret Army*.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] Most popular was "Louise" from the film *Innocents of Paris* (1929), which featured a number of times and was even sung in the "broken-French" language of Crabtree, who pronounced the title "Loo-woes".
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] Gruber sang a number such as "Can't Help Lovin' Dat Man" from *Show Boat* or "(I Got a Woman Crazy for Me) She's Funny That Way" by Neil Monet and Richard A.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] He gazed at René in a slightly lustful manner, replacing lyrics such as "woman" and "she" with "boy" and "he".
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] He caused a particular sensation with his straight version of Noël Coward's "Mad About the Boy".
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] Helga also sometimes stripped to a rather raunchy version (arranged by Roy Moore) of the latter tune.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] Captain Bertorelli could be seen singing "'O Sole Mio (It's Now or Never)"; and the British airmen in a prisoner of war camp could be seen singing "Hitler Has Only Got One Ball".
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] In 1986, Gorden Kaye and Vicki Michelle released a version of the hit song "Je t'aime... moi non plus".
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] The characters of Yvette and René could be heard talking and canoodling in a comic manner whilst the familiar musical "Je t'aime..."' melody played in the background.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] The song got to number fifty-seven in the UK Singles Chart.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] In 1985, Gorden Kaye and Carmen Silvera appeared in the Royal Variety Performance in character as René and Edith, and sang "I Remember It Well" from *Gigi*.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] The show gave rise to a successful touring stage-show featuring most of the TV cast.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] This ran from 1986 to 1992, and included three London stage runs as well as international tours.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] In January 1990, Gorden Kaye suffered serious head injuries in a car accident.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] As a result, his understudy, John Larson, played the part in a London Palladium production.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] Kaye had a dent in his forehead for the rest of his life from a piece of wood that smashed through the car window.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] He wanted to end the television show after his accident, but was persuaded by Jeremy Lloyd to continue.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] In Australia Gorden Kaye's part was played by Australian comedian/impressionist Max Gillies (later, Gorden Kaye repaid the favour when he took over Max Gillies' role in another play in Australia, when Max Gillies was unable to take part).
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] The show was last performed for a summer season at Bournemouth's Pier Theatre in 1996.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] In 2007 Gorden Kaye, Sue Hodge and Guy Siner reprised their roles in a production of the stage show in Brisbane, Australia.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] They were joined by Steven Tandy as Colonel von Strohm and Jason Gann as Herr Flick.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] A new touring show, based on the 1992 tour written by David Croft and Jeremy Lloyd, opened at the Gordon Craig Theatre in Stevenage, Hertfordshire on 29 August 2008 before going on a national tour the following year.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] Vicki Michelle reprised her role as Yvette Carte-Blanche.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] The cast also included Jeffrey Holland playing Rene Artois and his wife Judy Buxton playing Michelle Dubois.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] Other cast members included Robin Sebastian as Gruber, James Rossman as Herr Flick, Nell Jerram as Private Helga Geerhart and Claire Andreadis as Mimi Labonq.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] The theatrical version is also frequently performed by amateur theatre companies in the UK and elsewhere.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] A sequel stage show, 'Allo 'Allo 2 – The Camembert Caper, written by David Lovesy, David Pibworth and Steve Clark, adapted from the TV series and approved by the Croft and Lloyd estates was published by Concord Theatricals in September 2023.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] This is also available for theatre groups to perform worldwide.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] Exterior shooting took place in Norfolk, much of it at Lynford Hall.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] Between 1982 and 1987, and from 1989 to 1992, all interior scenes were filmed in front of a studio audience at the BBC Television Centre studios in London.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] For the fifth series, recorded from December 1987 to August 1988, production moved to BBC Elstree Centre in Studio D.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] With hopes for a US syndication deal, the BBC planned to make 26 new episodes of the sitcom; hence, a bigger space was needed for the production.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] Even though the US syndication deal did not go ahead as planned, production remained at BBC Elstree Centre for the remainder of the fifth series.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] With more space available, the outside set of Café Rene became a semi-permanent structure in the former ATV Garage building.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] The exact location supposed to be depicted in the show was kept vague.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] The town of Nouvion does exist, and it is near Abbeville, which was referenced in the show on several occasions.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] Road signs used as props in outdoor scenes of the show include signs for Caen, Orbec, Falaise, Livarot, and Pont l'Eveque — all consistent with a location in the department of Calvados, some 200 km to the west of the real Nouvion.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] In Australia, Roadshow Entertainment, under licence from the BBC began releasing the series on DVD in 2006, on a semi-annual basis.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] To date, all series have been released on DVD; only *The Return of 'Allo 'Allo!* TV special remains to be released.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] Universal Playback, under licence from the BBC, began releasing the series on DVD in 2002.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] In the UK six boxed sets with series 1–9 have been released, as well as a complete boxed set.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] The original UK releases have episode titles superimposed over the openings of the episodes (series 1–4).
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] The 2013 re-release of the complete series boxed set omits the majority, but not all of these superimposed titles.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] The American releases have no on-screen episode titles, reflecting the way that the shows were originally transmitted.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] In January 2004, BBC Worldwide began releasing the show itself on DVD in North America, distributed by Warner Bros., beginning with Series 1.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] The releases continued on a somewhat irregular basis (approximately twice-yearly).
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] A video game adaptation named *'Allo 'Allo!
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] Cartoon Fun* was released for the Amiga in 1993 by Alternative Software.
[src:bbc-one/allo-allo] It is a platform game where players control René.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The channel was launched on 2 November 1936 under the name **BBC Television Service**, which was the world's first regular television service with a high level of image resolution.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] It was renamed **BBC Television** in 1960 and used this name until the launch of the second BBC channel, BBC Two, in 1964.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The main channel then became known as **BBC1.** The channel adopted the current spelling of BBC One in 1997.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The channel's annual budget for 2024–2025 was £1.28 billion.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] It is funded by the television licence fee together with the BBC's other domestic television stations and shows uninterrupted programming without commercial advertising.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The television channel had the highest reach share of any broadcaster in the United Kingdom as at 2019, ahead of its traditional rival for ratings leadership ITV.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] In 2013, a study conducted across 14 countries by the polling organisation Populus found BBC One to be the station most favourably viewed by its country, with BBC Two coming in third place.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] BBC One is available via most major television providers in the United Kingdom.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The BBC began its own regular television programming from the basement of Broadcasting House, London, on 22 August 1932.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The channel officially began regular broadcasts on 2 November 1936 at three o'clock in the afternoon from a converted wing of the Alexandra Palace in London.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Initially, programmes ran from three o'clock to four o'clock in the afternoon and nine o'clock to ten o'clock in the evening.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Television director Gerald Cock described his rationale for the timings of the service as to "avoid eye strain" for home viewers in breaks between programmes, and to have a five-hour break between both periods in order not to interfere with home routines, such as mealtimes and children's bedtimes.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The BBC also depended on newsreels from other companies as it did not have a television news service of its own until 1948.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] BBC Television returned on 7 June 1946 at three o'clock in the afternoon.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Jasmine Bligh, one of the original announcers, made the first announcement, saying, "Good afternoon everybody.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Twenty minutes later, BBC Television again aired the Mickey Mouse cartoon that they had broadcast in 1939.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] It carried the 1948 Summer Olympics, which tested the limits of new television equipment, the most ambitious outside broadcast that the BBC had ever done to date.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The channel was made available outside of London for the first time on 17 December 1949, when the Sutton Coldfield transmitting station in the Midlands opened.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The BBC hoped for the service to reach 70% of the British population by 1952, then 80% by 1954.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The BBC made its first cross-country broadcast on 27 August 1950, crossing the English Channel in cooperation with its French counterpart RTF in Calais, lasting for one hour.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] From this experiment, the term "Eurovision" was coined, which was later adopted by the European Broadcasting Union as the name of its network, which in 1954 was already fully operational.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The BBC held a statutory monopoly on television broadcasting in the United Kingdom until Associated-Rediffusion, the first Independent Television (ITV) station, began to broadcast on 22 September 1955.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Lord Reith, which had long left his position at the corporation, compared its introduction to a plague at the House of Lords.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] While Reith's predictions did not come to pass, BBC Television's viewing share fell down to less than 30% by the end of the decade.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The competition quickly forced the channel to change its identity and priorities, following a large reduction in its audience, as noted in the 1962 Pilkington Report on the future of broadcasting.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Simultaneously, the Pilkington Report decided to award an additional television station to the BBC on the basis that ITV was in comparison lacking in serious programming.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] BBC Television became BBC1 when BBC2 launched on 20 April 1964, transmitting an incompatible 625-line image on UHF.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The only way to receive all channels was to use a complex "dual-standard" 405- and 625-line receiver with both a VHF and a UHF aerial (405-line-only sets became obsolete in 1985 when VHF transmissions ended).
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] BBC1 moved to purpose-built facilities at Television Centre on 20 September 1969.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Television News continued to use Alexandra Palace as its base and by early 1968 had even converted one of its studios to colour.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] In the weeks leading up to 15 November 1969, BBC1 unofficially transmitted the occasional programme in its new colour system in order to test it.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] At midnight on 15 November, simultaneously with ITV and two years after BBC2 had done so, BBC1 officially began 625-line PAL colour programming on UHF with a broadcast of a concert by Petula Clark.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Colour transmissions could be received in monochrome via monochrome 625-line sets until the end of analogue broadcasting.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Competition tactics with ITV flared up again in the early 1970s, when the channel opted to air its key sitcoms at 7:30 pm, countering *Coronation Street* (at the time airing two nights a week) and related drama series.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] During the early years of BBC2, some programmes made for the channel were repeated on BBC1, attracting higher attention there, such as *The Forsyte Saga* when it gained a repeat on this channel.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Between 1973 and 1977, BBC1 achieved an average audience share of 45% under Bryan Cowgill.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] This was the channel's most successful period in terms of audience share.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] On 30 December 1980, the BBC announced plans to introduce a new breakfast television service to compete with TV-am.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] They stated that the new show would be broadcast before TV-am but included the caveat that the new show would not launch until at least November 1981, whereupon new licence fee income could finance the necessary extension of broadcasting hours.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] On 17 January 1983, one year after originally planned, the first edition of *Breakfast Time* was shown on BBC1, becoming the first UK wide breakfast television service and continued to lead in the ratings until 1984.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] In 1984, Bill Cotton become managing director of Television at the BBC, and set about overhauling BBC1, which had been slated with poor home grown shows, its heavy reliance on US imports, with *Dallas* and *The Thorn Birds* being BBC1's highest rated programmes and ratings being over 20% behind ITV.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Cotton recruited Michael Grade to become Controller of BBC1 from 1 September 1984 the first time the corporation had recruited someone outside of the BBC, replacing Alan Hart.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The first major overhaul was to axe the unpopular *Sixty Minutes* current affairs programme: this was a replacement for the news and magazine show *Nationwide*.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Its replacement was the *BBC Six O'Clock News*, a straight news programme in a bid to shore up its failing early evening slot.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] It was believed the BBC were planning to cut short the evening news and move more light entertainment programming in from the 18:20 slot, but this was dismissed.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The Miss Great Britain contest was dropped, being described as verging on the too offensive after the January 1985 contest, with *World's Strongest Man* and *International Superstar* also being cancelled.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] BBC1 was relaunched on 18 February 1985 with a new look, new programming including *Wogan* and *EastEnders*, and a revised schedule to help streamline and maintain viewers throughout the course of the evening.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Grade started to gear most programmes to either on the hour or half past the hour, while *Panorama* and *Omnibus* were both moved after the *Nine O'Clock News*.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Grade was also determined to end the dated and inept BBC1 scheduling which was hampering the channel and holding back good programmes.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Grade said "When I took over BBC1, I discovered there were wonderful things, it was just a case of where to put them." *Wogan* had been scheduled for a 10 pm slot, but Grade moved it to a 7 pm slot as he believed the show had potential.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] From February to August 1985, a high number of American mini-series were broadcast while filming took place of a number of new home grown programmes, including *'Allo 'Allo!*, *In Sickness and in Health*, and *Open All Hours*.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Further improvement came about when the corporation strengthened its drama output costing £30 million, with eight new series, including *Howards' Way*, *All Creatures Great and Small*, *Hold the Back Page*, and *Bluebill*, along with the return of *Bergerac* and *Big Deal*.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The increase in the drama department was achieved by switching the money away from the administrative service over a three-year period, after BBC1 was criticised for failing to match ITV's output in drama.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] *EastEnders* was moved to a 19:30 slot, where it managed to soar to 20 million, helping the BBC1 audience share increase to nearly 50% for the first time since 1982.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] On 27 February 1985, *Doctor Who* was placed on an 18-month hiatus.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The BBC originally planned to axe the series as they wished to spend its budgets on new programming for the channel, but was forced to back down from public pressure and *Doctor Who* returned in September 1986.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] At the time Michael Grade and Jonathan Powell were blamed for the decision (Grade was the target of death threats).
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] On 9 September 1985, the long-standing children's programming block was overhauled and rebranded as *Children's BBC*, which gave it dedicated idents for the first time and had a live in-vision presenter, similar to rival ITV's Children's ITV block which had been running since January 1983.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Previously the BBC had broadcast children's programming using BBC1's team of regular duty announcers.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The launch presenter for this block, and thus the first Children's BBC presenter of the current format, was Phillip Schofield.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] On 23 May 1986, long-running lunchtime magazine show *Pebble Mill at One* was broadcast for the last time after being on air for 14 years.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] On 27 October 1986, BBC1 launched its daytime television schedules.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] During this time, both commercial analogue broadcasters, ITV and Channel 4 had officially begun stereo transmissions using the BBC-developed NICAM system.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Widescreen programming was introduced on digital platforms in 1998.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] For the first 50 years of its existence, with the exception of films and programmes purchased from the United States and elsewhere, almost all the channel's output were produced by the BBC's in-house production departments.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] This changed following the passing of the Broadcasting Act 1990, which required that 25% of the BBC's television output be out-sourced to independent production companies.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] By 2004, many popular BBC One shows were made for the channel by independents, but the in-house production departments continued to contribute heavily to the schedule.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] In December 1991 *Wogan* was to be cancelled, due to falling ratings against a number of ITV shows, in which *Wogan* only managed six million viewers compared to double that for *This Is Your Life*, *The Krypton Factor* and *The $64,000 Question*.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Additionally an extra £40 million a year was spent on narrowing the gap on ITV's ratings lead, since a few months prior to this the channel had been criticised for its Autumn schedule, having tired formats, uninspiring scheduling of new programmes and poor scripts.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] *Wogan* was replaced with *Eldorado*, in early July 1992, but this was itself cancelled a year later.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] *Lois & Clark: The New Adventures of Superman* included in the Saturday night line up to increase variety.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Following the public disapproval of filling its schedule with 25% of repeats during the summer months of 1993, BBC1 agreed to broadcast an extra 110 hours worth of original programming over the same period during the summer in 1994, which included giving *EastEnders* an additional episode per week.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Efficiency savings of £25 million were found and redeployed to the new productions.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The savings were seen as a vindication for Producer Choice, the controversial internal market introduced in April 1993.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] By March 1999, the channel admitted defeat in its ratings war with ITV, with its spring line up emphasising more on serious factual and educational programmes, and drama.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] This change in strategy came about after continuing complaints that the channel was appealing to the lowest common denominator to increase viewership.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Reliance on docusoaps and the dropping of the vilified *Noel's House Party* were chastened by the hoax guests on *The Vanessa Show*.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Alan Yentob said "The spring package is to remind people of what the BBC is here for, range and ambition you won't find anywhere else at peak time".
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Lorraine Heggessey became Controller of BBC One, a post she took up on 1 November 2000.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] She had previously been sounded out about the job in 1997 following Michael Jackson's departure, but had turned down the opportunity as she felt she was then not yet experienced enough.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] During Heggessey's five years in charge, BBC One's audience share fell by 19.9%, to 23%, although this was in the context of declining audience figures across all British television channels due to increased competition from multichannel digital television.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] However, in 2001 BBC One overtook its main rival ITV in terms of annual audience share for the first time since the rival channel had launched in 1955, although much of this was down to the success of the channel's daytime television line-up, which had its own Controller: Jane Lush.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The moving of *Panorama* attracted criticism that BBC One was sidelining serious programming in favour of more populist output.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Heggessey publicly defended the decision, despite it not being hers, claiming that *Panorama*'s ratings would have "dwindled" in its previous slot.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Heggessey and the BBC's Controller of Drama Commissioning, Jane Tranter, took advantage of the weekday 21:00 slot opening up by moving the news to commission new popular drama output, such as the successful *Waking the Dead* (2000–2011) and *Spooks* (2002–2011).
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Immediately after her arrival, Heggessey ordered a review of the "Balloon" idents the channel had been using for its between-programme idents since 1997.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] In her opinion, the balloon was "slow and distant" and so, on 29 March 2002, after much speculation, she decided to abandon the "Balloon" idents (and the traditional "Globe" idents the channel had used in a variety of forms since 1963).
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] They were replaced by a new style of on-air identity for the channel, the "Rhythm & Movement" idents.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The new idents attracted criticism for going against the traditions of the channel and pandering to "political correctness", as they featured activities performed by people of various ethnicities.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The abandonment of a station clock, and perceived lack of a 'serious ident', also put the BBC in an embarrassing situation just one day into the new look with the death of the Queen Mother.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] One of Heggessey's most notable decisions and last major success at the channel was the recommissioning of the science-fiction drama series *Doctor Who*, which had been a popular hit in previous decades but ceased production in 1989.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Heggessey and Jane Tranter recommissioned the series in September 2003, after Heggessey had spent two years persuading the BBC's commercial arm, BBC Worldwide, to abandon their attempts to make a feature film version of the programme and allow it to instead return it to BBC One.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Heggessey did later concede in a 2005 interview with *The Independent* newspaper that arts programming had suffered a cutback under her control of BBC One.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] However, she did respond to this omission following criticism from the Board of Governors of the BBC by commissioning programmes such as the arts documentary series *Imagine...* (2003–present) and *A Picture of Britain* (2005).
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] On 14 February 2005 it was announced that Lorraine Heggessey was to leave the BBC to take up the post of Chief Executive at production company Talkback Thames.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Five months after her departure, BBC One was named "Channel of the Year" at the Edinburgh Television Festival, primarily on the strength of Heggessey's commissions such as *Strictly Come Dancing* and *Doctor Who*.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] His first full year in charge of the channel saw a year-on-year growth in the audience share, with a rise from 22.2% in August 2005 to 23.6% in August 2006.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] However, *Davina* was a critical and ratings disaster, which Fincham subsequently admitted was personally his fault, although he defended the strategy of experimenting with the BBC One schedule.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Fincham later found himself having to publicly defend the £18 million salary that the BBC paid Jonathan Ross in 2006, although Ross's BBC One work—primarily consisting of *Friday Night with Jonathan Ross*—formed only part of his overall BBC commitment.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The channel was named *Channel of the Year* at the 2007 Broadcast Awards.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Following its rebrand in March 2002, BBC One launched *The One to Watch* campaign, during which animated blocks created the word "The" and moved into the BBC logo.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Each new campaign incorporating the theme retained the same animated sequence.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] In May 2007, Fincham decided to drop *Neighbours*, an Australian soap opera, from BBC One after 21 years on the channel, when its producers, FremantleMedia significantly raised the price they wanted the BBC to pay for it in a bidding war.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Fincham commented that it was 'a big loss', but that BBC One would not pay 'the best part of £300 million'.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] *Neighbours* left the channel after the BBC's contract to show the programme ended on 8 February 2008, and moved to Channel 5 on 11 February 2008.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] *The Weakest Link* was moved from BBC Two to fill the gap, with the afternoon CBBC slot moving 20 minutes earlier.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] There was further controversy in July 2007 when Fincham was accused of misleading BBC One viewers.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The incident involved a clip from forthcoming documentary *A Year with the Queen* which was shown to journalists during a press conference.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Fincham admitted the error, but rejected calls that he should resign from his position as a result.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] His future was deemed uncertain following critical comments from Sir Michael Lyons, Chairman of the BBC Trust, and he resigned on 5 October 2007.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] In 2009, a report published by the BBC Trust found scheduling changes had led to a decrease in viewers.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] This was especially noticeable for *Blue Peter* and *Newsround*, two of CBBC's flagship programmes; *Blue Peter* which recorded its lowest viewing numbers since it started in 1958, and *Newsround* with fewer than 100,000 viewers compared to 225,000 in 2007.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] As part of the Delivering Quality First proposals submitted by the BBC in October 2011 and approved by the BBC Trust in May 2012, all children's programming on BBC One and Two would be moved permanently to the CBBC and CBeebies channels following the digital switchover.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The move was criticised by *Teletubbies* co-creator Anne Wood, who described the changes as "ghettoising children's programmes" and believe it was merely a cost-cutting measure.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Wood said "On the one hand it is inevitable.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] There is a certain amount of overlooking of the fact that children's programmes do get a wider audience than people are aware of ...
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] I have frequently had letters from older people who have enjoyed my programmes as much as children do.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] In 2012, the BBC out-bid ITV for the rights to air a *British* version of Dutch TV talent show *The Voice*.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The BBC paid £22 million for the rights to broadcast the show in the UK for two years.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] *The Voice UK* achieved good ratings for the BBC but ratings dropped towards the end of the first series and the second series.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] In 2013, *The Voice UK* was rescheduled to avoid a clash, and as a result, ratings have improved.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] In November 2015, it was announced that *The Voice UK* would be moving to ITV from 2017, especially because of the ITV plc ownership of franchise owner, Talpa Media.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] On 8 October 2013, the BBC announced plans to launch a one-hour time shift of the channel, named BBC One +1.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The channel would have replaced BBC Three in 2016.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] However, on 30 June 2015, the BBC Trust rejected the plans for a BBC One +1 channel as they stated that it would be at the expense of commercial rivals.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] BBC One HD at launch did not offer regional variations, and therefore the channel could not broadcast during regional programming slots, most noticeably the local news programmes.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The BBC Trust admitted that this was due to technical and financial constraints, but the BBC announced on 6 June 2011 that the national variations of BBC One Northern Ireland, BBC One Scotland and BBC One Wales, would become available from 2012.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] On 24 October 2012, Northern Ireland received the first variation.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] A Scottish variation launched on 14 January 2013, followed by a Welsh variation on 29 January 2013.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] On 16 July 2013, the BBC indicated that it also wants to launch regional variants of BBC One HD across England; however, this would require the approval of the BBC Trust, with a proposal due to be presented within six months.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] On 18 November 2013, the Northern Irish regional variant of BBC One HD was swapped with the SD channel on Sky's EPG for HD subscribers.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] This was followed by the Welsh and Scottish variants on 10 December.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] On 24 March 2014, BBC One Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland HD launched on Freesat, Sky and Virgin Media outside the regions they were originally seen in.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] On 31 March 2016, BBC One HD in England moved from channel 141 on the Sky electronic programme guide to channel 115, a position vacated by BBC Three, which had been switched to internet-only six weeks earlier.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Changes in Scotland, Wales, and Northern Ireland were also scheduled but delayed for 'technical reasons' and eventually BBC Two HD was moved to channel 115 in those regions.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] On 22 November 2022, the BBC announced that BBC One would finally be regionalised on their HD channels.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] This move started on Sky Glass, followed by Virgin Cable, and then in the 2023 new year, HD programmes were launched on satellite.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] With the launch of the HD channels, this also meant the closure of the SD channels.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] SD channels were shut on satellite 24 hours after the launch of the HD channel, and were moved up to the Channel 1/Channel 101 slot on the EPG.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Viewers with older standard definition set-top boxes would no longer be able to receive BBC One.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] All BBC satellite channels in standard definition closed on 8 January 2024.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] BBC Alba HD, BBC Red Button 1 HD and BBC Parliament HD also launched on satellite at a similar time.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The BBC and Freesat launched a website with a guide, telling users how to make sure they are upgraded at www.hdsatelliteupgrade.co.uk.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Regional programming began on BBC One HD in certain regions on 22 March 2023; it began in the remaining regions on 26 April 2023, as well as regionalised versions launching on Freeview that same day.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] With a mission to provide programmes for all licence-fee payers, it has sport, news, current affairs, and documentaries.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] It has historically broadcast children's programmes (now taken from CBBC and CBeebies).
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Since 1990, the BBC has had to commission output from other domestic suppliers.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Although the statutory target remains 25% for independent production companies to contribute programming for BBC One, 33% of output was made by them in 2010–11.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The quota of original programming in peak times is set at 90%; however, 100% of peak programming was original in 2010–11.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Over the whole day, the total for the same year was 89%, against a quota of 70%.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] All three main news bulletins have a lead over their rival programmes on ITV and other terrestrial or cable channels.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] During the weekend period, three separate bulletins around these three time periods are broadcast and vary in length from 10 to 25 minutes.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] BBC One has broadcast overnight simulcasts from the BBC News Channel since 1997; the latter in turn simulcasts the majority of all regular BBC One bulletins.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] When BBC One is broadcasting a BBC News special, it hands some of its daytime programming to BBC Two.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Each year 159 hours of current affairs programmes are broadcast on BBC One, including *Panorama* and *Watchdog*.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Politics is also covered, with programmes including *Question Time* and *This Week* shown.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] *Crimewatch*, a programme appealing for help in unsolved crimes, is broadcast monthly.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] BBC One shows 1,880 hours of factual and learning programming annually.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] This includes a wide range of shows such as nature documentaries such as *Planet Earth* as well as lifestyle-format daytime programmes and a number of *reality television* formats and the *One Life* strand.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] BBC One broadcasts 1,036 hours of drama each year, more than any other BBC channel.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] There are four half-hour episodes of *EastEnders* each week (not shown on Friday), plus the hospital drama *Casualty*.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Other popular dramas on BBC One include crime dramas such as *New Tricks*, a programme of which even episode repeats have beaten ITV ratings on numerous occasions.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] BBC One has traditionally been the home of children's television: *Blue Peter* had been broadcast on the channel prior to the Children's BBC strand, and sections such as the pre-school *Watch with Mother* being transmitted on the channel for several decades.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] This became more pronounced with the launch of Children's BBC, later renamed "CBBC".
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] This new strand was broadcast primarily on BBC One in the late afternoons, as well as Saturday and Sunday mornings also such as *Going Live!* and *Live & Kicking*, each lasting two to three hours.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The launch in 2002 of dedicated digital channels for this content —the CBBC and CBeebies channels —did not affect this provision.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Combined with BBC Two, the channel broadcast 2,195 hours of children's programmes in 2010, mostly in the late afternoons on weekdays.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Saturday morning children's programming moved to BBC Two in 2006 following a three-month trial.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Sports coverage on BBC One includes Premier League football highlights on *Match of the Day*, the Wimbledon Championships, the London Marathon, and other international athletics and swimming events, the Olympic Games, Rugby league, Rugby Union, Snooker tournaments, the American Super Bowl, and more.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The BBC showed the 2010 FIFA World Cup, splitting the group stage matches with ITV.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The BBC had first pick of matches from the second round.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Programming on this channel costs an average of £162,900 per hour.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] British and international films are broadcast for 654 hours each year on BBC One.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] This is mainly late-night fillers with some box office hits at Christmas and holiday periods.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Sometimes on a Saturday afternoon there is a film on to fill the gap between entertainment shows but very rarely has there been one in that slot.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Entertainment programming on BBC One includes game shows such as the *National Lottery*, *Total Wipeout*, *Strictly Come Dancing* and chat shows such as *The Graham Norton Show*.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The annual 92 hours of religious programming comprise weekly editions of live *Songs of Praise*, Christian services and other shows from independent production companies.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Mentorn Oxford produces *Heart and Soul*, described as "a new multi-faith programme featuring a panel and a studio audience", followed by *Life from the Loft* which is made by the Leeds-based company True North.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] In 2005 BBC One was criticised for reducing the amount of religious programming, previously 101 hours per year.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] BBC One broadcasts many comedy programmes, often on Friday nights.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] These have included the stand-up comedy show *Live at the Apollo*, sitcom *Outnumbered*, and satirical quiz show *Have I Got News for You*.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Saturday evening is also a popular slot for a comedy show such as *Michael McIntyre's Big Show* and *The Armstrong and Miller Show*.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Since BBC Three became an online-only service in 2016, BBC One broadcast some BBC Three programming, particularly such as *People Just Do Nothing*, *Cuckoo*, *RuPaul's Drag Race UK* and *This Country*.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] In March 2019, BBC1 had a dedicated timeslot for BBC3 as a programming block.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The block was dropped when BBC Three returned as a linear TV channel in early 2022, but BBC One continues to broadcast some BBC Three programmes.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] As the weekly popular music chart programme *Top of the Pops* was dropped in 2006 (except for the Christmas Day edition), BBC One broadcast 49 hours of music and arts programming in 2010.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The majority of this was *Imagine*, presented by Alan Yentob, and classical music concerts, in particular some of the *BBC Proms*.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] BBC One's daytime line-up was a major factor in it overtaking ITV as the most popular channel in 2000, a position it has retained, even though ITV achieves a higher audience share during the daytime.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The morning daytime line-up consists of lifestyle shows, such as *Morning Live*, *Homes Under the Hammer* and *Bargain Hunt*, the afternoons contain drama with daily soap *Doctors* and classic US drama, such as *Diagnosis: Murder*.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Sometimes a drama such as *Land Girls* is shown in the afternoons.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Between 15:25 and 17:35 was the CBeebies/CBBC broadcasting strand, with its own visual identity.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Historically, BBC One's most popular daytime programme was *Neighbours*, with audience figures approaching five million.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] On 11 February 2008, BBC One dropped *Neighbours* and the programme was broadcast on Channel 5 until 2022.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] In its place was the quiz show *The Weakest Link*, which was moved from BBC Two, and later replaced in 2011 by *Pointless*.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Children's programmes were broadcast from 15:05 - 17:15 to accommodate this change and this continued until December 2012 when the afternoon CBeebies/CBBC block was axed.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] On 16 May 2012, the BBC announced the children's block of shows would be moved permanently to CBBC and CBeebies upon the completion of the Digital switchover.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] In its place appear the game show *Perfection*, plus *Escape to the Country* and *Put Your Money Where Your Mouth Is*.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] In February 2022, the BBC confirmed that *EastEnders* will get a Monday to Thursday slot at 7:30 pm with the programme due to form part of a BBC soap hour which will include a repeat of daytime soap *Doctors* on BBC Two at 7 pm.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Due to this decision, the BBC One regional slot will be pushed back half an hour to 8 pm on Wednesdays, where it will feature programmes such as documentary series *We Are England*.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] BBC One's identity has been symbolised by a globe shown on its idents for much of its existence.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The first BBC ident was shown on 2 December 1953, known as the Bat's Wings.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] In 1962 this was replaced by a map of the UK shown between programmes, and in 1963 the globe appeared, changing in style and appearance over the next 39 years.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Most notably, on 18 February 1985, the "Computer Originated World" was introduced.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] This was a computer-animated globe with the land coloured gold and the sea a transparent blue, giving the impression of a glass globe.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] This was replaced by the "Virtual Globe" on 16 February 1991.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] On 4 October 1997, the globe became a red, orange and yellow hot-air balloon, coloured to resemble a globe.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] It was filmed flying around various places in the UK.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] On 29 March 2002, the globe was replaced by a series of visual identities, "idents", consisting of people dancing in various styles.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] These were replaced on 7 October 2006 by the 'circle' idents.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] According to the BBC, the circle symbol both represents togetherness (unity) and acts as a link to the classic globe icon used for 39 years.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] They ran until 4 December 2016, when that year's Christmas idents launched.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] On 1 January 2017, a new ident set launched, based on the theme of "oneness".
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The idents were reinstated on 19 July 2021 when the UK government lifted some Coronavirus restrictions until the new Lens idents arrived the following year on 1 April 2022.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] BBC One is not one unified channel, but has several different feeds that form a television network.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] BBC One has individual continuity and opt-outs for Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] Each variant maintains the BBC One logo with the addition of the constituent country name beneath it.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] In England, each region has an individual regional news and current affairs programme opt-out as well as a limited amount of continuity.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] *UK Today*, a news programme, was shown nationally to digital viewers in place of regional programmes when they were unavailable to broadcast on analogue television.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The programme was discontinued in 2002 and replaced by a transmission of *BBC London News* until all BBC regions were made available digitally.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] BBC One Scotland has the greatest level of variation from the generic channel, owing to BBC Scotland scheduling Scottish programming on the main BBC Scotland channel, rather than on BBC Two Scotland which closed in 2019.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] BBC One Scotland variations include the soap opera *River City* and the football programme *Sportscene*, the inclusion of which causes programming to be displaced or replaced.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] BBC One Wales was considered a separate channel by the BBC as early as its launch in the mid-1960s, appearing as BBC Wales.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] BBC One (Northern Ireland) is widely available in Ireland on cable and satellite television.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] BBC One (especially the London feed) is also available on cable and IPTV in the Netherlands, Belgium, Switzerland, Monaco and Liechtenstein.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The channel is registered to broadcast within the European Union/EEA through the Luxembourgish Broadcasting Regulator – ALIA.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] On 27 March 2013 it was offered by British Forces Broadcasting Service (BFBS) to members of HM Forces and their families around the world, replacing the BFBS 1 TV channel, which already carried a selection of BBC One programmes.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] All feeds of BBC One in both SD and HD are broadcast unencrypted on the Astra 2E and 2G satellites, allowing viewing across Belgium, the Netherlands, the Republic of Ireland and parts of France, Germany and Spain.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The BBC announced in May 2008 that it had achieved its aim for all programming to have subtitles for viewers with hearing difficulties.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The BBC also offers audio description on some popular BBC One programmes for visually impaired viewers.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] The percentage of the BBC's total television output with audio description available is 10%, having been increased from 8% in 2008.
[src:bbc-one/bbc-one] In 2016, the controller of BBC One would be promoted to oversee all BBC channels, with the channel controller roles being entirely scrapped in 2020, in favour of a focus on digital streaming.
